{"title_page": "Oscar Yuston", "text_new": "{{short description|Argentine sports shooter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Oscar Yuston\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Argentine\n| sport          = [[Shooting sports|Sports shooting]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1939|2|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Oscar Yuston''' (born 14 February 1939) is an Argentine [[Shooting sports|sports shooter]]. He competed in the [[Shooting at the 1976 Summer Olympics \u2013 Mixed 25 metre rapid fire pistol|men's 25 metre rapid fire pistol event]] at the [[1976 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/yu/oscar-yuston-1.html |title=Oscar Yuston Olympic Results |accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yuston, Oscar}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Argentine male sport shooters]]\n[[Category:Olympic shooters of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in shooting]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games gold medalists for Argentina]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for Argentina]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-sportshooting-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Argentine sports shooter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Oscar Yuston\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Argentine\n| sport          = [[Shooting sports|Sports shooting]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1939|2|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Oscar Yuston''' (born 14 February 1939) is an Argentine [[Shooting sports|sports shooter]]. He competed in the [[Shooting at the 1976 Summer Olympics \u2013 Mixed 25 metre rapid fire pistol|men's 25 metre rapid fire pistol event]] at the [[1976 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/yu/oscar-yuston-1.html |title=Oscar Yuston Olympic Results |accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yuston, Oscar}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Argentine male sport shooters]]\n[[Category:Olympic shooters of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in shooting]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games gold medalists for Argentina]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for Argentina]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-sportshooting-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oscar_Yuston"}
{"title_page": "Ole Bull Academy", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=February 2014}}\n\nThe '''Ole Bull Academy'''<ref>{{cite book|author1=Sidsel Karlsen|author2=Heidi Westerlund|author3=Heidi Partti|author4=Solbu Einar|editor1-last=Veblen|editor1-first=Kari K.|editor2-last=Messenger|editor2-first=Stephen J.|editor3-last=Silverman|editor3-first=Marissa|editor4-last=Elliott|editor4-first=David J.|title=Community Music Today|date=2013|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|location=Lanham, MD|page=47|chapter=Community Music in the Nordic Countries: Politics, Research, Programs, and Educational Significance}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Grimley|first1=Daniel M.|title=Grieg: Music, Landscape and Norwegian Identity|date=2006|publisher=Boydell Press|location=Rochester, NY|page=163}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Fiddle Making Workshop of the Ole Bull Academy|url=https://www.felemakeriet.no/english/|website=Ole Bull Akademiet|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref> ({{lang-no|Ole Bull Akademiet}}, established 1977 in [[Voss]], [[Norway]]) is a Norwegian music college that offers college-level courses on [[Norwegian folk music]] and [[folk dance]]. Today, the Academy educates about 700 students annually, and over 9000 students had taken a course at the Academy in 2003. Near the end of 2009 the figure was 12,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://idmmei.isme.org/index.php/institutions?pid=132&sid=2727:Ole-Bull-Academy-Ole-Bull-Akademiet-Voss |title=Ole Bull Academy (Ole Bull-Akademiet), Voss |publisher=ISME.org |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nThe idea of an academy came from [[Ole Bull]] in 1863. He wished an academy that was based on Norwegian folk music, and a [[ballet]] inspired by Norwegian village dances. The idea was turned into reality by [[Sigbj\u00f8rn Bernhoft Osa]] in 1977, First by course in the \"sl\u00e5ttespill\" for students at the [[Norges Musikkh\u00f8gskole]] and [[Bergen Musikkonservatorium]]. According to the website of the Academy, teaching follows the old principle from folk music: \"From ear to ear, string to string, from throat to choke\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snl.no/Ole_Bull_Akademiet |title=Ole Bull Akademiet Biography |language=Norwegian |publisher=[[Store Norske Leksikon]] |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n\nThe teaching is organized in courses, usually by a week. A fixed two-year course for performers was established by [[Griegakademiet]] from 1996, and is leading to a bachelor's degree in combination with study points from [[University of Bergen]]. In 2009 a Bachelor's Degree was started in Traditional dance together with the RFF-center and [[Norges Teknisk-Naturvitenskapelige Universitet|NTNU]]. Study within [[education]] will be given by [[Stord/Haugesund University College]]. The Academy also collaborates with music education institutions in the [[Denmark]], [[Sweden]] and [[Finland]]. Also, are granted teaching [[ethnology]] and [[music history]], and it is held international English language summer courses.\n\nIn collaboration with \u00abVoss Spelemannslag\u00bb the Academy manages \u00abVoss Folkemusikksamling\u00bb. Furthermore publish the books and records, and runs music workshops. They hold the \u00abOsafestivalen\u00bb every autumn, and manages the fund and fiddle collection after [[Sigbj\u00f8rn Bernhoft Osa]]. Furthermore, it owns and operates the student home \u00abKringsj\u00e5\u00bb, developed containing the administration department, teaching rooms and concert hall in 1994, and in 2004 it was extended by several more teaching rooms, practice rooms and office. The Academy is currently funded by both [[Norwegian Ministry of Culture and Church Affairs]], [[Hordaland County Municipality|Hordaland County]] and the municipality of [[Voss]]. Rector in 2009 was Gunnar Stubseid, who led a staff of seven employees.\n\n== References ==\n{{portal|Norway|Music}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://origo.no/-/venue/show/19758_ole-bull-akademiet Origo.no om akademiet]\n*[http://www.kulturnett.no/institusjoner_og_kulturminner/institusjon_og_kulturminne.jsp?id=T11104679&pageid=4 Kulturnett.no om akademiet]\n*[http://www.snl.no/Ole_Bull_Akademiet Snl.no om akademiet]\n*[http://www.folkemusikk.no/ole-bull-akademiet.4607708-137442.html Folkemusikk.no om akademiet]\n*[http://www.ntnu.no/eksternweb/multimedia/archive/00045/info_opptak_45418a.pdf NTNU om eit samarbeidsstudie med akademiet]\n\n{{coord|60.6301|6.4212|type:edu_region:NO|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Norwegian folk music]]\n[[Category:Music schools in Norway]]\n[[Category:Education in Bergen]]\n[[Category:1977 establishments in Norway]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=February 2014}}\n\nThe '''Ole Bull Academy'''<ref>{{cite book|author1=Sidsel Karlsen|author2=Heidi Westerlund|author3=Heidi Partti|author4=Solbu Einar|editor1-last=Veblen|editor1-first=Kari K.|editor2-last=Messenger|editor2-first=Stephen J.|editor3-last=Silverman|editor3-first=Marissa|editor4-last=Elliott|editor4-first=David J.|title=Community Music Today|date=2013|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|location=Lanham, MD|page=47|chapter=Community Music in the Nordic Countries: Politics, Research, Programs, and Educational Significance}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Grimley|first1=Daniel M.|title=Grieg: Music, Landscape and Norwegian Identity|date=2006|publisher=Boydell Press|location=Rochester, NY|page=163}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Fiddle Making Workshop of the Ole Bull Academy|url=https://www.felemakeriet.no/english/|website=Ole Bull Akademiet|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref> ({{lang-no|Ole Bull Akademiet}}, established 1977 in [[Voss]], [[Norway]]) is a Norwegian music college driven to impart knowledge about the [[Norwegian folk music]] and [[folk dance]] to students at college and university level. Today, the Academy educates about 700 students annually, and over 9000 students had taken a course at the Academy in 2003. Near the end of 2009 the figure was 12,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://idmmei.isme.org/index.php/institutions?pid=132&sid=2727:Ole-Bull-Academy-Ole-Bull-Akademiet-Voss |title=Ole Bull Academy (Ole Bull-Akademiet), Voss |publisher=ISME.org |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nThe idea of an academy came from [[Ole Bull]] in 1863. He wished an academy that was based on Norwegian folk music, and a [[ballet]] inspired by Norwegian village dances. The idea was turned into reality by [[Sigbj\u00f8rn Bernhoft Osa]] in 1977, First by course in the \"sl\u00e5ttespill\" for students at the [[Norges Musikkh\u00f8gskole]] and [[Bergen Musikkonservatorium]]. According to the website of the Academy, teaching follows the old principle from folk music: \"From ear to ear, string to string, from throat to choke\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snl.no/Ole_Bull_Akademiet |title=Ole Bull Akademiet Biography |language=Norwegian |publisher=[[Store Norske Leksikon]] |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n\nThe teaching is organized in courses, usually by a week. A fixed two-year course for performers was established by [[Griegakademiet]] from 1996, and is leading to a bachelor's degree in combination with study points from [[University of Bergen]]. In 2009 a Bachelor's Degree was started in Traditional dance together with the RFF-center and [[Norges Teknisk-Naturvitenskapelige Universitet|NTNU]]. Study within [[education]] will be given by [[Stord/Haugesund University College]]. The Academy also collaborates with music education institutions in the [[Denmark]], [[Sweden]] and [[Finland]]. Also, are granted teaching [[ethnology]] and [[music history]], and it is held international English language summer courses.\n\nIn collaboration with \u00abVoss Spelemannslag\u00bb the Academy manages \u00abVoss Folkemusikksamling\u00bb. Furthermore publish the books and records, and runs music workshops. They hold the \u00abOsafestivalen\u00bb every autumn, and manages the fund and fiddle collection after [[Sigbj\u00f8rn Bernhoft Osa]]. Furthermore, it owns and operates the student home \u00abKringsj\u00e5\u00bb, developed containing the administration department, teaching rooms and concert hall in 1994, and in 2004 it was extended by several more teaching rooms, practice rooms and office. The Academy is currently funded by both [[Norwegian Ministry of Culture and Church Affairs]], [[Hordaland County Municipality|Hordaland County]] and the municipality of [[Voss]]. Rector in 2009 was Gunnar Stubseid, who led a staff of seven employees.\n\n== References ==\n{{portal|Norway|Music}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://origo.no/-/venue/show/19758_ole-bull-akademiet Origo.no om akademiet]\n*[http://www.kulturnett.no/institusjoner_og_kulturminner/institusjon_og_kulturminne.jsp?id=T11104679&pageid=4 Kulturnett.no om akademiet]\n*[http://www.snl.no/Ole_Bull_Akademiet Snl.no om akademiet]\n*[http://www.folkemusikk.no/ole-bull-akademiet.4607708-137442.html Folkemusikk.no om akademiet]\n*[http://www.ntnu.no/eksternweb/multimedia/archive/00045/info_opptak_45418a.pdf NTNU om eit samarbeidsstudie med akademiet]\n\n{{coord|60.6301|6.4212|type:edu_region:NO|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Norwegian folk music]]\n[[Category:Music schools in Norway]]\n[[Category:Education in Bergen]]\n[[Category:1977 establishments in Norway]]\n", "name_user": "Vagabond nanoda", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copyedit.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ole_Bull_Academy"}
{"title_page": "Skarloey Railway", "text_new": "{{short description|Fictional railway which featured in books by Rev  W Awdry}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{primary sources|date=February 2020}}\n{{More footnotes|date=August 2019}}\n}}\n[[Image:Maps-sodor-railways-amoswolfe.svg|thumb|250px|A map of the Island of Sodor showing the railway system &ndash; the Skarloey Railway is shown in red.]]\n{{Skarloey Railway RDT|collapsed=yes}}\n[[Image:Maps-skarloey-railway-amoswolfe.png|thumb|250px|Map of the Skarloey Railway]]\nThe '''Skarloey Railway''' is a [[fictional]] [[narrow gauge railway]] on the [[Sodor (fictional island)|Island of Sodor]]. It appeared in [[#In_The_Railway_Series_(in_the_books)_2|8 books]] of ''[[The Railway Series]]'', by [[W.V. Awdry|Rev. W. Awdry]] and [[Christopher Awdry]],<ref name=FourLittleEngines>{{Cite book|title=[[List of Railway Series Books#Four Little Engines|Four Little Engines]]|last=Awdry|first=Wilbert|authorlink=Wilbert Awdry}}</ref><ref name=LittleOldEngine>{{Cite book|title=[[List of Railway Series Books#The Little Old Engine|The Little Old Engine]]|last=Awdry|first=Wilbert|authorlink=Wilbert Awdry}}</ref><ref name=GallantOldEngine>{{Cite book|title=[[List of Railway Series Books#Gallant Old Engine|Gallant Old Engine]]|last=Awdry|first=Wilbert|authorlink=Wilbert Awdry}}</ref><ref name=VeryOldEngines>{{Cite book|title=[[List of Railway Series Books#Very Old Engines|Very Old Engines]]|last=Awdry|first=Wilbert|authorlink=Wilbert Awdry}}</ref><ref name=GreatLittleEngines>{{Cite book|title=[[List of Railway Series Books#Great Little Engines|Great Little Engines]]|last=Awdry|first=Christopher|authorlink=Christopher Awdry}}</ref><ref name=NewLittleEngine>{{Cite book|title=[[List of Railway Series Books#New Little Engine|New Little Engine]]|last=Awdry|first=Christopher|authorlink=Christopher Awdry}}</ref><ref name=DukeTheLostEngine>{{Cite book|title=[[List of Railway Series Books#Duke the Lost Engine|Duke the Lost Engine]]|last=Awdry|first=Wilbert|authorlink=Wilbert Awdry}}</ref><ref name=MountainEngines>{{Cite book|title=[[List of Railway Series Books#Mountain Engines|Mountain Engines]]|last=Awdry|first=Wilbert|authorlink=Wilbert Awdry}}</ref>  and in [[#In_Thomas_&_Friends_(on_television)|99 episodes]] of the [[Television programme|Television]] adaptation of ''The Railway Series'', ''[[Thomas & Friends]]''.\n\nIn the stories, the railway runs from the main line at Crovan's Gate to the passenger terminus at Skarloey. Beyond Skarloey the line continues to the [[Fictional locations in The Railway Series#Skarloey_Slate_Mines|Skarloey]] [[slate]] [[quarry]].<ref name=SodorMaps>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041211115812/http://www.pegnsean.net/~railwayseries/mapsection.htm|title=Maps of Sodor|accessdate=11 December 2004}}</ref> Its is run by the Thin Controller, and its chief engineer is Ivo Hugh. The line was inspired by the [[Talyllyn Railway]] in Wales, where Rev. W. Awdry worked as a volunteer guard in the 1950s. The Talyllyn railway was owned by [[Henry Haydn Jones|Sir Haydn Jones]] (the [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Merioneth]] \u2013 the county which the Talyllyn Railway is in), who inspired the character of Sir Handel Brown in the books.\n\n==(Fictional) History==\nThe [[W.V. Awdry|Rev. W Awdry]] based his stories on real incidents on the real railways. In order to ensure consistency and accuracy, Awdry developed a 'history' for the Island of Sodor and its railways, which was published to accompany the series.  The history was set in context, and dates were determined to be consistent with the real world.\n\nIn the case of the Skarloey Railway, its history closely parallels that of the [[Talyllyn Railway]] in Wales. According to the \"research\" by the Rev. Awdry, the line began as a [[plateway]] and was opened in 1806 to collect [[copper ore]] and later [[slate]] from the local [[quarry|quarries]]. It was worked by gravity and carried mineral traffic that was shipped from Balladswail. Following the [[Ffestiniog Railway|Ffestiniog Railway's]] lead in 1863, James Spooner was engaged in surveying a line for steam locomotives. It was also planned to develop passenger traffic for tourists to the Springs at Skarloey where there would be hotels and guest houses.\n\nIt was later realized that the line could carry visitors to the local landmarks of Skarloey (which means 'Lake in the Woods') and Rheneas ('Divided Waterfall'). Like all railways at this time, it was powered by [[horse]]s, but by 1865 the railway's owners decided they needed [[locomotive|steam engines]] to help out. They ordered two engines from the locomotive builders [[Fletcher Jennings Ltd]] in Whitehaven, England. These engines were [[Skarloey]] and [[Rheneas]].\n\nSkarloey and Rheneas worked hard for many years, but eventually, the demand for slate decreased due to cheaper slate being imported from Italy. After [[World War II]] the railway was in a poor state, and the old mines had become ammunition dumps. The owner, Sir Handel Brown, thought he would have to sell the railway. At this point, the railway was taken over by Mr. Peter Sam, who became the [[Thin Controller]]. With the help of Mr. Ivo Hugh and a number of volunteers, they managed to keep the railway going. The railway's main source of income was now tourist traffic.\n\nEventually, Skarloey failed and Rheneas was left to manage alone, which he did admirably until [[Peter Sam]] and [[Sir Handel]] were bought from the [[Mid Sodor Railway]] to help out. Later they purchased [[Rusty the Diesel|Rusty]] and [[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Duncan|Duncan]].\n\nIt was around this time that the slate quarries were reopened. The [[slate]] from these quarries was pure and free from metallic impurities, which meant it was in demand as other slate demand fell.\n\nIn 1965 (the year that ''[[List of Railway Series Books#Very Old Engines|Very Old Engines]]'' was published) the railway celebrated the [[century|100th birthday]] of Skarloey and Rheneas with the opening of a new [[branch line]] to Lakeside by the Duke of Sodor. A second triumph came in 1969 when [[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Duke|Duke]] was saved and brought to the railway, where he was repaired and now works the passenger trains.\n\nSince the centenary celebrations of 1965, the railway has purchased a new diesel, ''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Fred|Fred]]''. It has also built a new steam engine, ''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Ivo Hugh|Ivo Hugh]]'', who was built in ''[[List of Railway Series books#New_Little_Engine|New Little Engine]]''.<ref name=NewLittleEngine/>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Characters==\n===Locomotives===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Crovan's Gate Ensemble 1995.jpg|thumb|The ensemble at Crovan's Gate: On the front are Duncan, Skarloey, Sir Handel and Peter Sam. On the back row are Duke and Rheneas.]] -->\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!No.\n!Skarloey locomotive\n!Real life equivalent\n!Real life equivalent's railway\n!Notes\n|-\n|1\n|''[[Skarloey]]''\n|''[[Talyllyn (locomotive)|Talyllyn]]''\n|''[[Talyllyn Railway]]''\n|Originally an [[0-4-0]] without a cab, later had trailing wheels added to improve stability \u2013 making the loco an [[0-4-2]]. At this time, he had a cab added. Named after the northern passenger terminus of the Skarloey Railway, [[Skarloey (station)|Skarloey station]].\n|-\n|2\n|''[[Rheneas]]''\n|''[[Dolgoch (locomotive)|Dolgoch]]''\n|''[[Talyllyn Railway]]''\n|[[0-4-0]] built without a cab, later had one added. Named after [[Rheneas (station)|Rheneas station]] on the Skarloey Railway.\n|-\n|3\n|''[[Sir Handel]]''\n|''[[Sir Haydn (locomotive)|Sir Haydn]]''\n|''[[Talyllyn Railway]]''\n|''Falcon'' from the [[Mid Sodor Railway]]. A '''[[Falcon Works|Falcon]]''' type engine, renamed after his new Railway's owner, [[Sir Handel (person)|Sir Handel]].\n|-\n|4\n|''[[Peter Sam]]''\n|''[[Edward Thomas (locomotive)|Edward Thomas]]''\n|''[[Talyllyn Railway]]''\n|''Stuart'' from the [[Mid Sodor Railway]]. A ''Tattoo'' class engine built by [[Kerr, Stuart and Co.]], renamed after his new Railway's Controller, [[Peter Sam (person)|Peter Sam]], who is also known as ''The Thin Controller''.\n|-\n|5\n|''[[Rusty (locomotive)|Rusty]]''\n|''[[Midlander (locomotive)|Midlander]]''\n|''[[Talyllyn Railway]]''\n|built by [[Ruston & Hornsby|'''Rust'''on & Hornsb'''y''']]\n|-\n|6\n|''[[Duncan (locomotive)|Duncan]]''\n|''[[Douglas (locomotive)|Douglas]]''\n|''[[Talyllyn Railway]]''\n|Introduced as a spare engine after Peter Sam's accident with trucks.\n|-\n|7\n|''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Ivo Hugh|Ivo Hugh]]''\n|''[[Tom Rolt (locomotive)|Tom Rolt]]''\n|''[[Talyllyn Railway]]''\n|Named after the Railway's first General Manager, who helped to keep the railway running during the early preservation era. Only features in the [[The Railway Series|books]]; in the [[Thomas & Friends|TV series]] Freddie carries his number.\n|-\n|8\n|''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Duke|Duke]]''\n|''[[Ffestiniog Railway rolling stock#Locomotives|Prince]]''\n|''[[Festiniog Railway]]''\n|From the [[Mid Sodor Railway]].\n|-\n|9\n|''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Fred|Fred]]''\n|''[[Alf (locomotive)|Alf]]''\n|''[[Talyllyn Railway]]''\n|Never seen, only mentioned. Rusty once pulled a weedkiller train for him.\n|-\n|\n|''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Bertram|Bertram]]''\n|''[[Ffestiniog Railway#Locomotives|Palmerston]]''\n|''[[Ffestiniog Railway]]''\n|Appears in the [[Thomas the Tank Engine and Friends|TV Series]] only.\n|-\n|\n|''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Mighty Mac|Mighty Mac]]''\n|''[[Fairlie|Double Fairlie]] locomotives''\n|''[[Ffestiniog Railway]]''\n|Only appears in the [[Thomas & Friends|TV series]].\n|-\n|7\n|''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Fearless Freddie|Fearless Freddie]]''\n|''[[Russell (locomotive)|Russell]]''\n|''[[Welsh Highland Railway]]''\n|Only appears in the [[Thomas & Friends|TV series]]. Carries the same number as Ivo Hugh does in the [[The Railway Series|books]].\n|-\n|22\n|''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Luke|Luke]]''\n|''[[Peter Pan (locomotive)|Peter Pan]]''\n|''[[Leighton Buzzard Light Railway]]''\n|Only appears in the [[Thomas & Friends|TV series]]. [[Kerr, Stuart and Company#Narrow gauge designs|Kerr Stuart 'Wren' Class]].\n|}\n\n==== Livery ====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!No.\n!Name\n![[The Railway Series|Railway Series]] livery\n![[Thomas & Friends]] livery\n|-\n|1\n|''[[Skarloey]]''\n|[[Scarlet (color)|Bright red]] with [[blue]] lining, [[Gold (color)|gold]] name painted on [[boiler]] and [[Gold (color)|gold]] number painted on [[bunker]], in a [[black]] circle with [[Gold (color)|gold]] edge.\n|\n|-\n|2\n|''[[Rheneas]]''\n|[[Scarlet (color)|Bright red]] with [[blue]] lining, [[Gold (color)|gold]] name painted on [[boiler]] and [[Gold (color)|gold]] number painted on [[bunker]], in a [[black]] circle with [[Gold (color)|gold]] edge.\n|[[Vermillion]]\n|-\n|3\n|''[[Sir Handel]]''\n|[[Scarlet (color)|Bright red]] with [[blue]] lining, [[Gold (color)|gold]] name painted on [[boiler]] and [[Gold (color)|gold]] number painted on [[bunker]], in a [[black]] circle with [[Gold (color)|gold]] edge.\n|Dull [[sky blue]]\n|-\n|4\n|''[[Peter Sam]]''\n|[[Scarlet (color)|Bright red]] with [[blue]] lining, [[Gold (color)|gold]] name painted on [[boiler]] and [[Gold (color)|gold]] number painted on [[bunker]], in a [[black]] circle with [[Gold (color)|gold]] edge.\n|Dull [[Shades of green#Bright green|green]]\n|-\n|5\n|''[[Rusty (locomotive)|Rusty]]''\n|[[Black]], with [[white]] name painted on side.\n|[[Rust]]-[[Surface texture|textured]] [[Shades of orange#Orange (color wheel)|orange]].\n|-\n|6\n|''[[Duncan (locomotive)|Duncan]]''\n|[[Scarlet (color)|Bright red]] with [[blue]] lining, [[Gold (color)|gold]] name painted on [[boiler]] and [[Gold (color)|gold]] number painted on [[bunker]], in a [[black]] circle with [[Gold (color)|gold]] edge.\n|[[Yellow]] with gold and black lining\n|-\n|7\n|''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Ivo Hugh|Ivo Hugh]]''\n|[[Scarlet (color)|Bright red]] with [[blue]] lining, [[Gold (color)|gold]] name painted on [[boiler]] and [[Gold (color)|gold]] number painted on [[bunker]], in a [[black]] circle with [[Gold (color)|gold]] edge.\n|N/A\n|-\n|7\n|''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Fearless Freddie|Fearless Freddie]]''\n|N/A\n|[[Gray]] with [[black]], [[gold]] and [[red]] lining.\n|-\n|8\n|''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Duke|Duke]]''\n|[[Maroon]], same as on [[Mid Sodor Railway]]\n|[[Maroon]], same as on [[Mid Sodor Railway]]\n|-\n|9\n|''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Fred|Fred]]''\n|Not mentioned\n|N/A\n|-\n|22\n|''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Luke|Luke]]''\n|N/A\n|[[Green]]\n|-\n|\n|''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Bertram|Bertram]]''\n|N/A\n|[[Maroon]], same as ''Duke''\n|-\n|\n|''[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Mighty Mac|Mighty Mac]]''\n|N/A\n|[[Royal blue]] with [[yellow]] and [[red]] stripes\n|}\n\nIn [[The Railway Stories]] [[books]], all of the steam engines are painted the same bright red colour with a simple blue lining except for [[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Duke|Duke]] (who retained the  paint from his days on the [[Mid Sodor Railway]]) and [[Rusty (locomotive)|Rusty]], who is painted charcoal-black. Unusually, the engines did not have nameplates; their names were just painted directly in gold on the side of the saddle tank or boiler, as to had been the case on the [[Talyllyn Railway]] before the [[Talyllyn Railway Preservation Society]] took over. The other diesels are painted dark-grey. The steam locomotive livery features lots of polished brass-work and is largely unchanged since the opening of the railway (judging by the illustrations in ''[[List of Railway Series Books#Very Old Engines|Very Old Engines]]'', although these show a more elaborate blue and yellow lining scheme).\n\nIn the [[Thomas & Friends]] [[TV series]], all of the engines, apart from [[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Duke|Duke]], are painted in completely different colours. This was presumably to assist the show's young fans in identifying the different engines. In the TV series, [[Railway engines (Thomas the Tank Engine and Friends)#Skarloey|Skarloey]] is painted bright red (as in the books) with white and yellow lining (blue in the books); [[Railway engines (Thomas the Tank Engine and Friends)#Rheneas|Rheneas]] was painted vermillion; [[Railway engines (Thomas the Tank Engine and Friends)#Sir Handel|Sir Handel]] and [[Railway engines (Thomas the Tank Engine and Friends)#Peter Sam|Peter Sam]] retained the colors that they wore when they were named Falcon and Stuart, on the [[Mid Sodor Railway]] (blue and green respectively); [[Railway engines (Thomas the Tank Engine and Friends)#Rusty|Rusty]] was painted rust-orange (which was the reason for his naming, according to a Thomas the Tank Engine annual); [[Railway engines (Thomas the Tank Engine and Friends)#Duncan|Duncan]] was painted yellow with gold and black lining; and [[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Duke|Duke]] kept his [[Mid- Railway Series dark red-brown..\n\n===Carriages===\nAgnes, Ruth, Lucy, Jemima and Beatrice are based on Talyllyn Railway carriages 1\u20135. The brake van Cora is based on the [[Corris Railway]] brake van that now runs on the Talyllyn.\nOpen coaches Ada, Jane and Mabel were rebuilt to a more conventional outline when funds became available and are based on Talyllyn Railway carriages 11, 12, 13. Gertrude and Millicent, bogie coaches, are based on Talyllyn Railway carriages 9 & 10. There are also longer coaches which are supposedly Talyllyn Railway carriages 16 and 18\u201323.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!No.\n!Skarloey carriage\n!Notes\n|-\n|1\n|''Agnes''\n|First class coach, is something of a snob.\n|-\n|2\n|''Ruth''\n|Third class coach.\n|-\n|3\n|''Lucy''\n|Third class coach\n|-\n|4\n|''Jemima''\n|Third class coach. Jemima appears to be hard of hearing in the book ''Four Little Engines''.\n|-\n|5\n|''Beatrice''\n|Guard's Van, also has a ticket office from which the guard may sell tickets.\n|-\n|6\n|''Cora''\n|Guard's Van, these days used for maintenance duties. Rescued from the Mid Sodor Railway.\n|-\n|7\n|''Ada''\n|Rescued from the Mid Sodor Railway.\n|-\n|8\n|''Jane''\n|Rescued from the Mid Sodor Railway.\n|-\n|9\n|''Mabel''\n|Mabel actually does not appear along with Ada and Jane. She appears two stories later, in ''Little Old Twins''. Rescued from the Mid Sodor Railway.\n|- \n|10\t\n|''Gertrude''\n|Bogie coach. Rescued with Millicent from the Mid Sodor Railway.\n|-\t\n|11\t\n|''Millicent''\n|Bogie coach with a guard. Rescued with Gertrude from the Mid Sodor Railway.\n|}\n\n====Livery====\nIn [[The Railway Stories]] books, the open carriages and guard's vans are painted blue (very similar to the British Rail [[rail blue]]). The enclosed carriages are painted off-white (upper half) and blue (lower).\n\n===Human Characters===\nThere have been a number of people associated with the railway who have appeared in the stories and TV Series.\n\n====Thin Controller====\nKnown properly as Mr. Peter Sam, the '''Thin Controller''' is the manager of the Skarloey Railway. A year before the arrival of Sir Handel and Peter Sam, he had to serve as [[Conductor (transportation)#Train guard|guard]] for all the trains.\n\nThe Thin Controller was introduced in ''[[List of Railway Series Books#Four Little Engines|Four Little Engines]]'', the tenth volume of [[the Railway Series]] and has now been introduced into the ''[[Thomas the Tank Engine & Friends]]'' TV series as [[Mr. Percival]], the narrow-gauge controller. He is based upon Edward Thomas general manager of the [[Talyllyn Railway]].\n\nAccording to ''[[List of Railway Series Books#Sodor: Reading Between the Lines|Sodor: Reading Between the Lines]]'', there are two thin controllers.\n\n*Mr. Peter Sam - The Thin Controller I\n*Mr. Roger Sam - The Thin Controller II\n\n====Sir Handel Brown====\nFormer owner of the railway, there have been two Sir Handel Browns:\n*Sir Handel Brown I\n*Sir Handel Brown II\n\n====Ivo Hugh====\n'''Ivo Hugh''' was one half of the two-man train crew in the final days of two-engine operation, alongside The Thin Controller. He was also the line's Chief Mechanical Engineer (CME) and became ''Rusty's'' driver, upon the diesel locomotive's arrival.\n\nHugh had retired by the time of ''[[List of Railway Series Books#New Little Engine|New Little Engine]]'' and had the honour of having the railway's new No. 7 named after him.\n\nHis son succeeded him as the new CME.\n\n====Other characters====\n*'''Mrs. Last''' &ndash; first appears in the book ''[[List of Railway Series Books#Four Little Engines|Four Little Engines]]''. She is a passenger who arrives late for her train. (She has not appeared in the TV series.)\n*'''The Refreshment Lady''' &ndash; Although she never receives a name in the stories, she is very popular with the passengers, selling drinks and ices on hot days. She was once left behind by Peter Sam by mistake, an incident inspired by [[Wilbert Vere Awdry|Reverend Awdry's]] own experience working as a guard on the Talyllyn Railway - albeit on that occasion, he admitted that the mistake was his fault rather than that of the engine!\n*'''Nancy the Guard's Daughter''' &ndash; A young girl who used to polish the engines. She was a friend to the engines, and Skarloey told her the story of his early life in the book ''Very Old Engines''. She is now grown up, and lives with her husband on the [[Isle of Man]].\n*'''Mr. Mack''' &ndash; former controller of the railway.\n*'''Mr. Bobbie''' &ndash; An engineer from [[Fletcher Jennings Ltd|Fletcher Jennings & Company]], who had worked on the construction of Skarloey. He was brought over when Skarloey misbehaved on his first arrival.\n*'''The Duke of Sodor''' &ndash; A British peer, and, jointly with the British monarch, the island's hereditary \"monarch\". He succeeded as a minor after his father was killed in the Second World War, and, as a young man in his twenties, appears only in the book ''[[List of Railway Series Books#Very Old Engines|Very Old Engines]]'', where he formally opens the loop line extension around the lake in 1965. He was introduced into the TV series with his correct original title of Earl of Sodor; he is only called \"Duke\" by some of the people of Sodor.\n*'''Lizzie and Kathy''' &ndash; These girls worked on the Skarloey Railway during the 1990s, again polishing the engines. Their parents worked on the Talyllyn Railway and came to the [[Island of Sodor]] on holiday.\n*'''Mr. Percival''' &ndash; The Thin Controller as portrayed in the ''[[Thomas and Friends]]'' TV series. He first appeared in Season 9.\n*'''Mrs. Percival''' &ndash; Mr. Percival's wife who first appears in season 10.\n*'''Percival Twins''' &ndash; Mr. and Mrs. Percival's children who appear in season 12.\n\n== Stations ==\n{{Skarloey Railway RDT}}\n=== In The Railway Series (in the books) ===\nThe names of the stations are not actually ever mentioned in the books (with the exception of one halt, Quarry Siding), and were referred to as \"the station by the lake\", \"the main station\", \"the first station\", \"the middle station\", \"the station by the waterfalls\", \"the top station\", etc.; thus, all their names are derived from [[List of Railway Series books#Companion_volumes|complementary publications about Sodor]], such as ''[[List of Railway Series Books#The Thomas the Tank Engine Man|The Thomas the Tank Engine Man]]''.<ref name=FourLittleEngines/><ref name=LittleOldEngine/><ref name=GallantOldEngine/><ref name=VeryOldEngines/><ref name=GreatLittleEngines/><ref name=NewLittleEngine/><ref name=DukeTheLostEngine/><ref name=MountainEngines/><ref name=ThomasTankMan>{{Cite book|title=[[List of Railway Series Books#The Thomas the Tank Engine Man|The Thomas the Tank Engine Man]]|last=Sibley|first=Brian|authorlink=Brian Sibley}}</ref>\n\nThe railway runs from Crovan's Gate, to Cros-ny-Cuirn, then stopping at Glennock, calling at Rheneas before starting the Lakeside loop line, which stops at Lakeside and finally the line ended at Skarloey.<ref name=SodorMaps/>\n\nAnother line branches off near Lakeside and goes to Ulfstead Castle.\n\nA further halt, called 'Quarry Siding' is mentioned in ''[[List of Railway Series books#The Little Old Engine|The Little Old Engine]]''. This halt is based on [[Quarry Siding Halt railway station|Quarry Siding halt]] on the Talyllyn Railway.<ref name=LittleOldEngine/>\n\n==== Crovan's Gate ====\nThis is the main station and southern terminus of the railway. The station complex is a compilation of all the stations at [[Tywyn]], which is the primary location and western terminus of the [[Talyllyn Railway]].\n\nThe passenger station at Crovan's Gate has a very typical layout for an interchange station. It has no specific real-life base, but could have been inspired by a proposed interchange station at [[Tywyn railway station|Tywyn mainline station]], which was the planned passenger terminus of the Talyllyn Railway, however the railway between [[Tywyn Wharf railway station|Tywyn Wharf Station]] and the mainline station was never built \u2014 for unknown reasons.\n\nThe workshops, locomotive sheds, and carriage shed, at Crovan's Gate, portrayed in all of the books involving the Skarloey Railway, are based on the workshops, locomotive sheds, and original carriage shed, at {{stnlnk|Tywyn Pendre}} on the [[Talyllyn Railway]].<ref name=\"FourLittleEngines\"/><ref name=\"LittleOldEngine\"/><ref name=\"GallantOldEngine\"/><ref name=\"VeryOldEngines\"/><ref name=\"GreatLittleEngines\"/><ref name=\"NewLittleEngine\"/><ref name=\"DukeTheLostEngine\"/><ref name=\"MountainEngines\"/>\n\nThe wharf at Crovans Gate, as portrayed in ''[[List of Railway Series books#The_Little_Old_Engine|The Little Old Engine]]'' and ''[[List of Railway Series books#Gallant_Old_Engine|Gallant Old Engine]]'', is based on the slate wharf at {{stnlnk|Tywyn Wharf}} on the [[Talyllyn Railway]].<ref name=\"LittleOldEngine\"/><ref name=\"GallantOldEngine\"/>\n\n==== Cros-ny-Curin ====\nCros-ny-Curin Station is a minor station about 3 miles away from Crovan's Gate.<ref name=SodorMaps/> It is situated at the point where the Skarloey Railway's current route starts deviating from the route of the 1806 horse-drawn plateway,<ref name=SodorMaps/> and is were the first incline was on the plateway.<ref name=\"ThomasTankMan\"/>\n\nThe station, as portrayed in ''[[List of Railway Series books#Four_Little_Engines|Four Little Engines]]'', is based on [[Rhyd-yr-onen railway station|Rhyd-yr-onen station]] on the Talyllyn Railway.<ref name=\"FourLittleEngines\"/>\n\nCros-ny-Curin's (fictional) etymology is that it was derived from 'Crossag-ny-cuirn', which means 'Little-Crossing-of-the-Mountain-Ash' in [[Sudric]] (Sodor's fictional language). This is a reflection of the meaning of 'Rhyd-yr-onnen' in [[Welsh language|Welsh]], which is 'Ash-ford'.<ref name=\"ThomasTankMan\"/>\n\n==== Glennock ====\nGlennock Station, often called 'the middle station', is a station approximately 11 miles from Crovan's Gate.<ref name=SodorMaps/>\n\nThe station's name is (fictionally) derived from 'Gleigh-knock', which means 'Blue-hill' in Sudric. This is the same as the Welsh meaning of [[Brynglas railway station|Bryn-Glas station]] on the Talyllyn Railway, which the station was partly based on.<ref name=\"ThomasTankMan\"/>\n\nGlennock station's positioning is based on Brynglas station on the Talyllyn Railway,<ref name=SodorMaps/><ref name=\"ThomasTankMan\"/> but the station itself, as portrayed in ''[[List of Railway Series books#Four Little Engines|Four Little Engines]]'', is based on [[Aberllefenni railway station|Aberllefenni station]] on the [[Corris Railway]].<ref name=\"FourLittleEngines\"/>\n\n==== Rheneas ====\nRheneas, often called 'The station by the waterfalls', is a station built for tourists traffic to the nearby waterfalls. It is approximately 21 miles away from Crovan's Gate.<ref name=SodorMaps/>\n\nRheneas station, as portrayed in ''[[List of Railway Series Books#Gallant Old Engine|Gallant Old Engine]]'', is based on [[Dolgoch railway station|Dolgoch station]] on the Talyllyn Railway.<ref name=\"GallantOldEngine\"/> 'Rheneas' means 'Divided Waterfall' in Sudric, and the station is so-named because of the nearby waterfalls, which themselves are based on the waterfalls near Dolgoch station on the Talyllyn Railway.\n\n==== Lakeside ====\nLakeside station is a station which is halfway round the ''Lakeside Loop''. It is approximately 23 miles away from Crovan's Gate.<ref name=SodorMaps/>\n\nThe station, and the associated ''Lakeside Loop Line'' which the station is on, was opened in ''[[List of Railway Series Books#Very Old Engines|Very Old Engines]]'', by the [[Duke of Sodor]]<ref name=\"VeryOldEngines\"/>\n\n==== Skarloey ====\nSkarloey station is the northern passenger terminus of the Skarloey Railway, although the railway continues to quarries further west. The station was built for tourists for the lake, and is approximately 22 miles from Crovan's Gate.<ref name=SodorMaps/>\n\nThe location of Skarloey station is based on a proposed station serving the hamlet of Dolffanog, a small hamlet north-east of [[Tal-y-llyn lake|Talyllyn lake]],<ref name=SodorMaps/> which featured in various 1970s proposals for an extension of the Talyllyn Railway to [[Tal-y-llyn Lake|Talyllyn lake]], [[Corris]], and [[Machynlleth]]. However, most of the station layout itself, as portrayed in ''[[List of Railway Series books#Four Little Engines|Four Little Engines]]'', is based on [[Abergynolwyn railway station]], the eastern terminus of the Talyllyn Railway, in its pre-1976 layout.<ref name=\"FourLittleEngines\"/>\n\nSkarloey's (fictional) eytymology is that the word came from 'Scacaloey', which itself was a corruption of 'Skogarloey', which means 'Lake-in-the-Woods' in Sudric. This is based on the meaning of 'Talyllyn' (Head-of-the-lake) in Welsh.<ref name=\"ThomasTankMan\"/>\n\n=== In Thomas And Friends (in the television series) ===\nThe railway in the television series also calls at Middle, Elephant Park, Tea Room, Bluebell Valley, Mountain Village, and Rumblin Bridge.\n\nIn the television series the railway runs from The Wharf, to west to Crovan's Gate, then north south of Rheneas where a line branches off and goes to Vicarstown, The main line continues the same path it does in the Railway Series.\n\n==Appearences==\nThe Skarloey Railway first appeared in [[List of Railway Series books#Four Little Engines|Four Little Engines]], the 10<sup>th</sup> book in [[The Railway Series]], in  October 1955. It has also featured in every season of the [[Thomas and Friends]] [[TV Show]] since [[Thomas & Friends (series 4)|season 4]]\n\n=== In The Railway Series (in the books) ===\nThe railway appeared in six books in [[The Railway Series]] \u2013 four in which it was the primary railway, and two in which it was not the primary focus, but played a significant supporting role.<ref name=\"FourLittleEngines\"/><ref name=\"LittleOldEngine\"/><ref name=\"GallantOldEngine\"/><ref name=\"VeryOldEngines\"/><ref name=\"GreatLittleEngines\"/><ref name=\"NewLittleEngine\"/><ref name=\"DukeTheLostEngine\"/><ref name=\"MountainEngines\"/>\n\n====Books where the Skarloey Railway is the primary focus====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Book No.\n!Book Name\n!Author\n|-\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#Four_Little_Engines|10]]''<ref name=\"FourLittleEngines\"/>\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#Four_Little_Engines|Four Little Engines]]''<ref name=\"FourLittleEngines\"/>\n|[[Wilbert Awdry|The Reverend Wilbert Awdry]]<ref name=\"FourLittleEngines\"/>\n|-\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#The_Little_Old_Engine|14]]''<ref name=\"LittleOldEngine\"/>\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#The_Little_Old_Engine|The Little Old Engine]]''<ref name=\"LittleOldEngine\"/>\n|[[Wilbert Awdry|The Rev. W. Awdry]]<ref name=\"LittleOldEngine\"/>\n|-\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#Gallant_Old_Engine|17]]''<ref name=\"GallantOldEngine\"/>\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#Gallant_Old_Engine|Gallant Old Engine]]''<ref name=\"GallantOldEngine\"/>\n|[[Wilbert Awdry|The Rev. W. Awdry]]<ref name=\"GallantOldEngine\"/>\n|-\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#Very_Old_Engines|20]]''<ref name=\"VeryOldEngines\"/>\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#Very_Old_Engines|Very Old Engines]]''<ref name=\"VeryOldEngines\"/>\n|[[Wilbert Awdry|The Rev. W. Awdry]]<ref name=\"VeryOldEngines\"/>\n|-\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#Great_Little_Engines|29]]''<ref name=\"GreatLittleEngines\"/>\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#Great_Little_Engines|Great Little Engines]]''<ref name=\"GreatLittleEngines\"/>\n|[[Christopher Awdry|Christopher Awdry]]<ref name=\"GreatLittleEngines\"/>\n|-\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#New_Little_Engine|40]]''<ref name=\"NewLittleEngine\"/>\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#New_Little_Engine|New Little Engine]]''<ref name=\"NewLittleEngine\"/>\n|[[Christopher Awdry|Christopher Awdry]]<ref name=\"NewLittleEngine\"/>\n|}\n\n====Books in which the Skarloey Raiway plays a supporting role====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Book No.\n!Book Name\n!Primary focus of the book\n!Author\n|-\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#Mountain_Engines|19]]''\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#Mountain_Engines|Mountain Engines]]''\n|[[Culdee Fell Railway]]\n|[[Wilbert Awdry|The Rev. W. Awdry]]<ref name=\"MountainEngines\"/>\n|-\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#Duke_the_Lost_Engine|25]]''\n|''[[List of Railway Series Books#Duke_the_Lost_Engine|Duke The Lost Engine]]''\n|[[Mid-Sodor Railway]] (also featured the [[Arlesdale Railway]] playing a supporting role)\n|[[Wilbert Awdry|The Rev. W. Awdry]]<ref name=\"DukeTheLostEngine\"/>\n|}\n\n===In Thomas & Friends (on television)===\nThe railway first appeared in [[Thomas and Friends - Season 4|the fourth season]] of [[Thomas the Tank Engine and Friends]]. At this time it closely followed the layout as portrayed in [[The Railway Series]] books, but from [[Thomas and Friends - Season 5|Season 5]] it differed significantly, deviating further from the books at the same time as the route of the [[North Western Railway (fictional)|North Western Railway]] was significantly altered.\n\nIt appears to be part of the North Western Railway rather than an independent line. It was run by [[the Fat Controller]], but from the ninth season onwards was under the control of \"Mr Percival\", a man strongly resembling the Thin Controller (as he is often referred to in the British version. Similarly, the American version occasionally refers to him as the Narrow Gauge Controller). Mr Hugh does not appear at all.\n\nThe railway has many more carriages in this version. Ada, Jane, Mabel, Gertrude and Millicent are entirely absent. Coaches resembling Agnes, Ruth, Lucy, Jemima, Beatrice and Cora do appear along with red coaches and coaches which are green upper half and cream lower half, but are unnamed and rarely speak. Ivo Hugh (the engine) has not appeared either, as the book in which he appeared (''New Little Engine'') has not been televised. However, the line has four new engines in this version named Bertram, Mighty Mac, \"Fearless\" Freddie, who acquired the number of Ivo Hugh, and Luke. Proteus was another engine originated from the TV series. He was never seen with the other engines, but Peter Sam once tried to find him and his magic lamp. He never succeeded. Years later, Peter Sam discovered a statue of Proteus that was put on display at the Showgrounds.\n\nThe Owner also does not appear.\n\n====Television episodes featuring the Skarloey Railway engines====\n*[[Thomas and Friends - Season 4|Season 4]]\n**Granpuff\