tom-kicks-nike-air-max-90-andy-warholmarilyn-monroe/ \"Custom Kicks \u2013 Nike Air Max 90 Andy Warhol/Marilyn Monroe\"] ''KicksOnFire.com'' February 24, 2010</ref>\n* [[Marilyn Monroe's pink dress]]\n* [[6126 (clothing line)|6126 by Lindsay Lohan]]: named after Monroe's birthdate\n* [[Warnaco Group]]: Warner's Marilyn Monroe intimate apparel line (1996)<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1997/02/10/business/an-undergarment-maker-hopes-the-marilyn-monroe-image-has-not-lost-its-sizzle.html?pagewanted=1 \"An undergarment maker hopes the Marilyn Monroe image has not lost its sizzle\"] ''New York Times'' (February 10, 1997) February 20, 2010</ref>\n* [[White dress of Marilyn Monroe]]\n* [[Zales]]: Marilyn Monroe Jewelry Collection <ref>[https://www.zales.com/collections/marilyn-monroe/c/011102073?cid=DIS-DBM-Prospecting-Corporate_Gifting&loadMore=2 \"Marilyn Monroe Jewelry Collection\"] ''zales.com'' Retrieved December 13, 2019</ref>\n\nSee also: ''Marilyn in Fashion: The Enduring Influence of Marilyn Monroe'' by Christopher Nickens and George Zeno, [[Running Press]] (2012), {{ISBN|0-762445-10-6|978-0-762445-10-3}}\n\n==Film==\n[[File:Marilyn Monroe photo pose Seven Year Itch.jpg|230px|thumb|right|While still in character, Monroe posed over the updraft of a New York City subway grating during the filming of ''The Seven Year Itch'' in Manhattan.<ref>{{cite web|first=Anne T|last=Donahue|title='That silly little dress': the story behind Marilyn Monroe's iconic scene|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2014/sep/15/marilyn-monroe-seven-year-itch-dress|website=[[TheGuardian.com]]|date=September 15, 2014|access-date=October 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\"The Seven Year Itch\" Scene and Its Legion of Blowing-Dress Imitators|url=https://www.flashbak.com/the-seven-year-itch-scene-and-its-legion-of-blowing-dress-imitators-377811/|website=flashbak.com|date=April 9, 2017|access-date=June 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Jesse|last=Gumbarge|title=10 Movies That Paid Homage To The Iconic Marilyn Monroe Subway Dress Scene|url=https://www.jarviscity.com/2014/07/14/marilyn-monroe-subway-dress-scene-homages/|website=Jarvis City|date=July 14, 2014|access-date=June 3, 2019}}</ref> The scene has been imitated on numerous occasions since the film was released.]]\n* ''[[The Apartment]]'': Dobisch tells Baxter he's trying to pick up a girl who looks like Monroe; the girl apes Monroe\n* ''[[Asso (film)|Asso]]'': (translated as ''Ace'') Silvia ([[Edwige Fenech]]) gets her white dress lifted by an airco like Monroe did in ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Back to the Future Part II]]'': Before [[Biff Tannen]] ([[Thomas F. Wilson]]) forced [[Marty McFly]]'s ([[Michael J. Fox]]) mother, [[Lorraine McFly|Lorraine]] ([[Lea Thompson]]), to marry him in an alternate version of 1985, Biff had dated Monroe, as shown by one video from the museum dedicated to his life.<ref>{{cite web |first=Seb |last=Patrick |title=Back to the Future: 88 Things You Missed in the Trilogy|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/back-to-the-future/241535/back-to-the-future-trilogy-things-you-missed/page/0/1|work=[[Den of Geek]]|date=July 3, 2018|access-date=October 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Cristina|last=Everett|title=18 hidden gems in 'Back to the Future II' \u00a7 Biff's many loves |url=https://ew.com/gallery/back-to-the-future-hidden-gems/#biffs-many-loves |website=[[EW.com]]|date=October 21, 2015|access-date=October 25, 2018}}</ref>\n* ''[[Birds of Prey (2020 film)|Birds of Prey]]'' (2020): [[Harley Quinn]]<ref>{{cite web|first=Dirk|last=Libbey|title=How Harley Quinn's Birds of Prey Performance Nods At Marilyn Monroe|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2481425/how-harley-quinns-birds-of-prey-performance-nods-at-marilyn-monroe |website=CinemaBlend|date=October 2, 2019|accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref>([[Margot Robbie]]) does a brief tribute to Monroe in her parody of \"Diamonds are a Girl's Best Friend\" from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes''\n* ''[[Blades of Glory]]'': Fairchild skates as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Blonde Ambition]]'': Katie apes the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Bordello of Blood]]'': Lilith apes the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Broken Embraces]]'': Lena apes Monroe\n* ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'': Ali Rose sings ''Diamond's Are a Girl's Best Friend'' from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' while Nikki and Georgia lip-synched the Monroe version, then Rose finished it with her own vocals\n* ''[[Calendar Girl (1993 film)|Calendar Girl]]'': Set in 1962, it tells the story about three young men (Roy, Scott and Ned) who go on a trip to Hollywood by fulfilling their dreams of meeting Marilyn Monroe. It has similarities to the real-life stories of Gene Scanlon who in 1953 with a friend crossed America and had a date with Monroe for which she paid the bill for.\n* ''[[Capote (film)|Capote]]'': Capote tells a reporter about a visit he paid to Monroe\n* ''[[Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen]]'': Lola is dressed as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch'' in a fantasy sequence.\n* ''[[Cool World]]'': Holli sings the title song of ''[[Let's Make Love]]''\n* ''[[Date Movie]]'': Julia Jones apes Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Death Becomes Her]]'': Monroe in her pink outfit from ''[[Gentlemen Prefer Blondes (1953 film)|Gentlemen Prefer Blondes]]''<ref>[https://www.garboforever.com/Garbo_Forever_Films-03.htm GarboForever \u2013 Death Becomes Her]</ref> dancing with [[Andy Warhol]] appeares at Helen's big party scene.\n* ''[[Deck the Halls (2006 film)|Deck the Halls]]'': the Finch's Christmas tree angel apes the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Don't Tell Mom the Babysitter's Dead]]'': As Sue Ellen \"Swell\" Crandell and her siblings (Kenny, Melissa, Zach and Walter) leave ''[[Chuck E. Cheese's|Chuck E. Cheese]]'', they witness their dead babysitter's (Mrs. Sturak) ''[[Buick]]'' getting stolen by three drag performers who are dressed as Marilyn Monroe (from ''[[The Seven Year Itch]]''), [[Liza Minnelli]] and [[Dolly Parton]]<ref>[http://www.iamnotastalker.com/2014/02/03/chuck-e-cheeses-from-dont-tell-mom-the-babysitters-dead/ Chuck E. Cheese's from ''Don't Tell Mom the Babysitter's Dead]</ref>\n* ''[[Fade to Black (1980 film)|Fade to Black]]'': Binford is obsessed with Monroe\n* ''[[Finding Graceland]]'': Byron and Elvis meet a Monroe look-a-like\n* ''[[Goodbye, Norma Jean]]'': The film is based on the life of Monroe\n* ''[[Goodnight, Sweet Marilyn]]'': A follow up of the 1976 film ''Goodbye, Norma Jean''\n* ''[[The Goddess (1958 film)|The Goddess]]'' (1958): based loosely on Monroe's life\n* ''[[Grease 2]]'': Paulette is obsessed with Monroe and [[John F. Kennedy]]'s alleged affair\n* ''[[Hercules (1997 film)|Hercules]]'' (1997): a [[Muse]] apes the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[The House Bunny]]'': Shelly apes Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Inappropriate Comedy|InAPPropriate Comedy]]'': In the skit \"Above the Grate\", [[Lindsay Lohan]] stands on an air vent much like Marilyn Monroe's famous scene from ''The Seven Year Itch'' while a man named Peeping Tom ([[Vince Offer]]) watches her from underneath as she then whips out two handguns and \"settles the score with the media\"<ref>[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=acT73n9NZ38 Lindsay Lohan InAPPropriate Comedy Movie Clip!]</ref><ref>[http://www.gawker.com/5600950/lindsay-lohan-shoots-paparazzi-with-guns-in-comedy-sketch Lindsay Lohan Shoots Paparazzi with Guns in Comedy Sketch]</ref>\n* ''[[I Heart Huckabees]]'': Dawn apes \"[[Happy Birthday, Mr. President]]\" in a Huckabees ad\n* ''[[Insignificance (film)|Insignificance]]'': The Actress ([[Theresa Russell]]) is based on Monroe\n* ''[[Kingpin (1996 film)|Kingpin]]'' (1996): Roy, Ish and Claudia are all set out to play all kinds of bowlers. First, they face off some steelworkers for whom Claudia distracts. Claudia stands over the ball dryer as her red skirt blows up in a parody of ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[L.A. Confidential]]'': a [[call girl]] has been \"cut\" to look like Monroe\n* ''[[The Ladies Man]]'' (1961): a girl Hebert delivers mail to apes Monroe\n* ''[[La La Land (film)|La La Land]]'': Traffic Dancer-Conductor's (Amanda Balen) yellow dress rises high in the opening scene as a brief filmic reference to Monroe's \"subway grate\" pose.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/13/nyregion/marilyn-monroe-skirt-blowing-new-york-film.html|title=The Lost Footage of Marilyn Monroe|last=Stapinski|first=Helene|date=January 13, 2017|access-date=November 14, 2018|work=The New York Times|quote=The new movie musical starring Ryan Gosling and Emma Stone, 'La La Land,' makes brief filmic reference to [that moment] in the opening number, with a young dancer\u2019s yellow dress blowing up.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thespec.com/whatson-story/7158366-rockingham-hamilton-dancer-is-upfront-in-la-la-land/|title=ROCKINGHAM: Hamilton dancer is upfront in La La Land |last=Rockingham |first=Graham |date=February 25, 2017|access-date=November 17, 2018|newspaper=[[The Hamilton Spectator]]}}</ref>\n* ''La Nueva Marilyn'': (translated as ''The New Marilyn'') a photographer (Jose Ballester) tries to make a new Marilyn Monroe out of his model (Teresa).\n* ''[[The Legend of Marilyn Monroe]]'': The film chronicles the life and career of the actress\n* ''[[L\u00e9on: The Professional]]'': In an attempt at cheering up L\u00e9on ([[Jean Reno]]), Mathilda ([[Natalie Portman]]) dresses up as Monroe and impersonates her by singing \"[[Happy Birthday, Mr. President]]\" seductively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lwlies.com/articles/leon-the-professional-mathilda-choker-natalie-portman/|title=The symbolic power of Mathilda's choker in L\u00e9on|last=Gosling|first=Sarah|date=August 2, 2017|access-date=December 10, 2018|work=[[Little White Lies (magazine)#Website|Little White Lies]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/69489/11-expert-facts-about-leon-professional|title=11 Expert Facts About ''L\u00e9on: The Professional''|last=Aquino|first=Tara|date=October 8, 2015|access-date=December 10, 2018|work=[[Mental Floss]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zimbio.com/Beyond+the+Box+Office/articles/UeZ2d6FD2ub/20+Things+May+Not+Know+L+Professional|title=20 Things You May Not Know About 'L\u00e9on: The Professional'|last=Robberson|first=Joe|date=September 15, 2014|access-date=December 10, 2018|work=[[Zimbio]]}}</ref>\n* ''[[A Life Less Ordinary]]'': Lewis works on a novel about Monroe and [[Robert F. Kennedy]]'s [[Legitimacy (family law)|love child]]\n* ''[[Little Voice (film)|Little Voice]]'': LV mimics Monroe's voice\n* ''[[Looney Tunes: Back in Action]]'': After Kate Houghton ([[Jenna Elfman]]) suggests pairing Bugs up with a hot female co-star, [[Bugs Bunny]] briefly disguises himself as Marilyn Monroe by saying in a soft, sultry voice \"Usually, I play the female love interest\"\n* ''[[Magic Mike]]'': Mike ([[Channing Tatum]]) dresses like Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''<ref>[http://www.vulture.com/2012/07/why-channing-tatum-wore-a-marilyn-monroe-costume.html Why Did Channing Tatum Wear a Marilyn Monroe Costume in ''Magic Mike'']</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FWtYyq3dXuk Magic Mike Channing Tatum as Marilyn Monroe]</ref>\n* ''[[Man on Fire (2004 film)|Man on Fire]]'' (2004): Rayburn owns a [[statue]] of Monroe aping the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Marilyn (1963 film)|Marilyn]]'': Based on the life of the actress and sex symbols\n* ''Marilyn's Man'': A story about Monroe's first husband James Dougherty\n* ''[[Mini's First Time]]'': Mini unwittingly apes the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[The Misfits (1961 film)|The Misfits]]'': Roslyn tries to keep Guido from looking at photos of Monroe Gay has taped inside a closet\n* ''[[Mister Lonely]]'': [[Samantha Morton]]'s character claims to be Monroe\n* ''[[Monkeybone]]'': Monkeybone [[Impersonation|impersonates]] Monroe\n* ''[[Monster (2003 film)|Monster]]'': Aileen recalls her childhood dream of being the next Monroe\n* ''[[Moulin Rouge!]]'': Satine sings ''Diamond's Are a Girl's Best Friend''<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GJjC1-ad6Cc Diamond's Are a Girl's Best Friend \u2013 Moulin Rouge (Cover)]</ref> from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes''\n* ''[[My Week with Marilyn]]'': Based on two books by [[Colin Clark (filmmaker)|Colin Clark]], ''My Week with Marilyn'' depicts the making of the 1957 film ''[[The Prince and the Showgirl]]'', which starred [[Marilyn Monroe]] ([[Michelle Williams (actress)|Michelle Williams]]) and [[Laurence Olivier]] ([[Kenneth Branagh]]). The film focuses on the week during the shooting of the 1957 film when Monroe was escorted around London by Clark ([[Eddie Redmayne]]), after her husband [[Arthur Miller]] ([[Dougray Scott]]) had returned to the United States.\n* ''[[Nobody Else But You]]'': The film focuses on the apparent suicide of a small-town woman who once though that she was the reincarnation of Monroe\n* ''[[Planet 51]]'': A picture of a green alien girl named Marilyn tries to hold down her white dress as a vent blows up air, just like the iconic shot from ''The Seven Year Itch'' (NOTE: She doesn't wear any shoes at all in the photo)\n* ''[[Pulp Fiction (film)|Pulp Fiction]]'': a waitress is dressed as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''Room to Rent'': Linda<ref>{{cite web|url=http://starslikemarilyn.blogspot.com/2009/05/juliette-lewis.html |title=The Stars like Marilyn Monroe Juliette Lewis|year=2009}}</ref> ([[Juliette Lewis]]) is a Marilyn Monroe impersonator from London\n* ''[[Same Time, Next Year (film)|Same Time, Next Year]]'': A still photo of the famous white dress blowing up from an air vent scene from ''The Seven Year Itch'' is part of a transitional montage\n* ''[[The Seven Year Itch]]'': Monroe is mentioned in one exchange.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brightwalldarkroom.com/2016/04/16/the-blonde-in-the-kitchen/|title=The Blonde in the Kitchen|last=Stent|first=Sabina|date=April 16, 2016|access-date=November 15, 2018|work=Bright Wall/Dark Room}}</ref>\n{{quote|Richard Sherman: [''continuing; crazed''] Because I can explain everything: the stairs, the cinnamon toast, the blonde in the kitchen.\n\nTom MacKenzie: [''interrupts; incredulous''] Wait! Wait a minute Dickey-Boy. What blonde in the kitchen?\n\nRichard Sherman: [''seething with contempt''] Oh, wouldn\u2019t you like to know! Maybe it\u2019s Marilyn Monroe!}}\n* ''[[The Shawshank Redemption]]'': The second poster Andy Dufresne ([[Tim Robbins]]) attaches on the wall of his cell is one of Marilyn Monroe in her \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/12-movies-to-watch-after-you-see-the-shawshank-redemption-f95394b4eb74/|title=12 Movies to Watch After You See 'The Shawshank Redemption'|last=Campbell|first=Christopher|date=September 12, 2014|access-date=October 25, 2018|work=[[Film School Rejects]]|quote=Andy\u2019s second poster is one of '''Marilyn Monroe''' in her iconic pose from a moment in ''The Seven Year Itch'', when her dress is blown up as she walks over a subway grating. This was the same as in the novella, as the character specifically had the Hayworth from 1948 to 1955. Then the Monroe from 1955 to 1960.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/this-is-how-long-andy-s-tunnel-was-in-the-shawshank-redemption-a6874701.html|title=This is how long Andy's tunnel was in The Shawshank Redemption|last=Loughrey|first=Clarisse|date=February 15, 2016|access-date=October 25, 2018|work=The Independent|quote=Knowing that the character, as the film states, began his tunnel in 1949; [NYC graphic designer Shahed] Syed utilised the various pin-up posters glimpsed in his cell as a mark of the passage of time: from Rita Hayworth (1949) to Marilyn Monroe (1957) to Raquel Welch (1966).}}</ref>\n* ''[[Shrek 2]]'': The Fairy Godmother makes Fiona ape the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[The Smurfs (film)|The Smurfs]]'': Smurfette apes the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Spice World (film)|Spice World]]'': During a dress-up montage, [[Geri Halliwell|Ginger Spice]] ([[Geri Halliwell]]) briefly posed as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''<ref>[http://www.starslikemarilyn.blogspot.com/2009/05/geri-halliwell.html The Stars like Marilyn Monroe Geri Halliwell]</ref>\n* ''[[Stroker Ace]]'': a pit crew member makes Pembrook ape the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Teaching Mrs. Tingle]]'': Jo Lynn gives her class presentation as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[The Tigger Movie]]'': Tigger dresses as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Tommy (1975 film)|Tommy]]'' (1975): The Preacher leads a cult based on Monroe\n* ''[[Town & Country (film)|Town & Country]]'': Auburn dresses as Monroe from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes''\n* ''[[Tropico (film)|Tropico]]'': Monroe appears alongside [[Adam]], [[Eve]], [[Jesus]], the [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Virgin Mary]], [[John Wayne]] and [[Elvis Presley]] in the [[Garden of Eden]] and recites lines from ''Some Like It Hot''\n* ''[[The Underground Comedy Movie]]'': [[Vince Offer]] pops up early as a guy named Peeping Tom in an underground lair who uses a fan to blow up the skirt of a Marilyn Monroe look-a-like ([[Gena Lee Nolin]]) as she strikes the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[White Palace (film)|White Palace]]'': Nora is a Monroe fan\n* ''[[The Woman in Red (1984 film)|The Woman in Red]]'': Charlotte unwittingly apes the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Wonder Boys (film)|Wonder Boys]]'': James steals the jacket Monroe wore the day she married Joe DiMaggio from Gaskell, who is obsessed with the DiMaggio-Monroe marriage\n* ''[[Wrongfully Accused]]'': Ryan Harrison wears a kilt and has it blown up from under him just like Monroe\n* ''[[Younger and Younger]]'': Younger has a vision of a girl aping Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Zapped!]]'': Barney makes a girl at the prom ape the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n\n==Graphic novels==\n* ''Deadpool'' by [[Gerry Duggan (writer)|Gerry Duggan]] and [[Brian Posehn]] (2013) Deadpool disguises himself as Marilyn Monroe, to kill a reanimated John F. Kennedy.\n\n==Literature==\n* [[Alvah Bessie]]: ''The Symbol'' (1966), based on Monroe's life\n* [[Truman Capote]]: \"A Beautiful Child\" from ''[[Music for Chameleons]]'' (1980)\n* [[Mort Castle]]: ''I Am Your Need'' (2001)\n* [[Douglas Coupland]]: ''[[Polaroids from the Dead]]'' (1996)\n* [[Peter Golenbock]]: ''7: The Mickey Mantle Novel'' (2007), Monroe and [[Mickey Mantle]] have an affair\n* [[Edward Gorman]]: ''The Marilyn Tapes'' (1995)\n* [[Doris Grumbach]]: \"The Missing Person\" (1981)\n* [[Allan Gurganus]]: ''Blessed Assurance'' (1990)\n* [[Michael Korda]]: ''The Immortals'' (1992)\n* [[Paul Levinson]]: \"Marilyn and Monet\" (2017)\n* [[Carole Morin]]: ''Dead Glamorous: the Autobiography of Seduction and Self Destruction'' (1996), a poetic account of the fascination of charismatic suicides including Marilyn, [[Ian Curtis]], and [[Sylvia Plath]]\n* [[Graham Masterton]]: ''Ikon'' (1982)\n* [[Norman Mailer]]: ''[[Marilyn: A Biography]]'', ''Of Women and Their Elegance'' (1980)\n* [[Joyce Carol Oates]]: ''[[Blonde (novel)|Blonde]]'', and \"Three Girls\" (1996)\n* [[Andrew O'Hagan]]: ''The Life and Opinions of Maf the Dog, and of His Friend Marilyn Monroe'' (2010)\n* [[John Rechy]]: ''Marilyn's Daughter'' (1989)\n* [[Lee Siegel (professor and novelist)|Lee Siegel]]: ''Who Wrote the Book of Love?'' (2005)\n\nSee also: ''Mondo Marilyn: An Anthology of Fiction and Poetry'' Richard Peabody and Lucinda Ebersole (Eds), [[St. Martin's Press]] (1995), {{ISBN|0-312-11853-8|978-0-312-11853-2}}\n\nSee also: ''Marilyn: Shades of Blonde'' [[Carole Nelson Douglas]] (ed.), Tor Books (1997), {{ISBN|0-312-85737-3|978-0-312-85737-0}}\n\n==Music==\n* [[Tori Amos]]: \"Father Lucifer\" references Monroe and Joe DiMaggio\n* [[Ray Anthony]]: \"My Marilyn\"\n* [[The Beatles]]: Monroe is on the cover of [[List of images on the cover of Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band|''Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band'']]\n* [[Dan Bern]]: \"Marilyn\"\n* [[Beyonc\u00e9]]: \"[[In da Club|Sexy Lil' Thug]]\" references Monroe\n* [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]]: \"Platinum Blonde\" references Monroe\n* [[Blue System]]:\n** \"The Wind Cries (Who Killed Norma Jean)\"\n** \"Good Night Marilyn\"\n* [[Bon Jovi]]: \"Captain Crash & the Beauty Queen From Mars\" references Monroe and Joe DiMaggio\n* [[David Bowie]]: \"Jean Genie\" references Monroe\n* [[Citizen Cope]]: \"Healing Hands\" references Monroe<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9XpKbC6oRuY \"Citizen Cope at the Cactus Cafe 'Healing Hands'\" ''youtube.com''] May 7, 2011</ref>\n* [[City Boy (band)|City Boy]]: \"Summer in the School Yard\" references Monroe\n* [[Sheryl Crow]]: \"[[If It Makes You Happy]]\" references Monroe\n* [[Culture Club]]: \"It's a Miracle\" references Monroe\n* [[CupcakKe]]: \"Best Dick Sucker\" references Monroe\n* [[Def Leppard]]: \"[[Photograph (Def Leppard song)|Photograph]]\"\n* [[Lana Del Rey]]:\n** \"Body Electric\" references Monroe\n** \"Children of the Bad Revolution\" references Monroe\n** a demo of \"Trash Magic\" references Monroe\n* [[The Distillers]]: \"[[Gypsy Rose Lee]]\" references Monroe\n* [[Everlast (musician)|Everlast]]: \"Whitey's Revenge\" references Monroe\n* [[Bryan Ferry]]: \"Goddess of Love\" references Monroe\n* [[Alexa Goddard]]: \"Marilyn\"\n* [[Grinderman]]: \"Palaces of Montezuma\" references Monroe and John F. Kennedy\n* [[Half Man Half Biscuit]]: \"99% of Gargoyles Look Like Bob Todd\" references Monroe\n* [[Teppo Hauta-aho]]/[[Edward Vesala]]: 1973 album ''Ode to Marilyn''\n* [[Faith Hill]]: \"[[The Secret of Life]]\" references Monroe\n* [[Michael Jackson]]: \"Tabloid Junkie\" references Monroe\n* [[Jay-Z]]: \"Hollywood\" references Monroe\n* \"[[We Didn't Start the Fire]]\" by [[Billy Joel]]<ref>{{cite web|title=We didn't start the fire|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2005/sep/29/highereducation.internationaleducationnews|website=[[TheGuardian.com]]|date=September 29, 2005|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lyrics to Billy Joel's 'We Didn't Start the Fire' With PM-Professor Joel|url=https://www.apnews.com/430699ab3b6524a3df492092bb640864|agency=[[Associated Press]]|location=New York City, New York, United States|date=January 19, 1990|access-date=October 25, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Elton John]]:\n** \"[[Candle in the Wind]]\"\n** \"Wrap Her Up\" (with [[George Michael]]) references Monroe\n* \"[[Lie to Me (Mikolas Josef song)|Lie to Me]]\" by [[Mikolas Josef]]<ref>{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Halpin|title='Lie to Me' lyrics \u2013 Mikolas Josef (Czech Republic, Eurovision 2018)|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2018/03/05/czech-republic-mikolas-josef/|work=[[Wiwibloggs]]|date=March 5, 2018|access-date=October 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mikolas Josef \u2013 Lie To Me Lyrics|url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/lie-to-me-lyrics-mikolas-josef.html|work=[[MetroLyrics]]|access-date=October 25, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Tommy Keene]]: \"My Mother Looked Like Marilyn Monroe\"\n* [[Alicia Keys]]: \"[[Girl on Fire (song)|Girl on Fire]]\" reference Monroe\n* [[The Kinks]]: \"Celluloid Heroes\" references Monroe\n* [[Kinky Friedman]]: \"Marilyn & Joe\"\n* [[Kool Keith]]: \"Livin' Astro\" references Monroe\n* [[Lady Gaga]]:\n** \"[[Dance in the Dark]]\" references Monroe\n** \"[[Do What U Want]]\" featuring [[R. Kelly]] references Monroe's alleged affair with John F. Kennedy\n** \"Nothing On (But The Radio)\" references Monroe\n** \"[[Government Hooker]]\" is about Monroe's alleged affair with John F. Kennedy {{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n* [[Laze & Royal]]: \"Marilyn Monroe\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HXz4C7D0F6k \"Laze & Royal \u2013 Marilyn Monroe (feat. Tyler Sherritt)\" ''youtube.com''] May 26, 2010</ref>\n* [[Phoebe Legere]]: \"Marilyn Monroe\"\n* [[Valery Leontiev]]: \"Marilyn\"\n* [[Amanda Lepore]]': \"Marilyn\"\n* [[Lil Xan]] featuring [[Charli XCX]]: \"Moonlight\" references Monroe\n* [[Jennifer Lopez]] featuring [[Nas]]: \"I'm Gonna be Alright\" references Monroe and Joe DiMaggio\n* [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]: \"[[Vogue (Madonna song)|Vogue]]\" references Monroe\n* [[Man From Delmonte]]: \"Beautiful People\" references Monroe and Joe DiMaggio\n* [[Marilyn Manson]] and his [[Marilyn Manson (band)|band]] is taken from Monroe and [[Charles Manson]]\n* [[Marina and the Diamonds]]: \"State Of Dreaming\" references Monroe\n* [[Ava Max]]: \"Salt\" references Monroe\n* [[Melanie Martinez (singer)]]: \"You Love I\" loops a quote Monroe gives in a 1960 interview backwards \n* [[Jessica Mauboy]] featuring [[Snoop Dogg]]: \"[[Get 'Em Girls (song)|Get 'Em Girls]]\" references Monroe\n* [[Metallica]]: \"[[The Memory Remains]]\" quotes a line from Monroe's character in ''[[The Misfits (1961 film)|The Misfits]]''\n* [[Minako Honda]]: \"Nen No Marilyn\"\n* [[Nicki Minaj]]: \"[[Marilyn Monroe (Nicki Minaj song)|Marilyn Monroe]]\"\n* [[K Camp]]: \"Marilyn Monroe\"\n* [[Kylie Minogue]]: \"Mr. President\" references Monroe\n* [[Misfits (band)|Misfits]]:\n** \"[[Who Killed Marilyn?]]\"\n** The band takes its name from ''[[The Misfits (1961 film)|The Misfits]]''\n* [[Maren Morris]]: \"[[Rich (Maren Morris song)|Rich]]\" referenced Monroe\n* [[Norma Jean (band)|Norma Jean]]: takes its name from Monroe's real name, Norma Jeane\n* [[Pauline Oliveros]]: \"To [[Valerie Solanas]] and Marilyn Monroe in Recognition of Their Desperation\" <ref name=\"Oliveros\">{{cite web | last=Oliveros | first=Pauline | title=To Valerie Solanas and Marilyn Monroe in Recognition of Their Desperation (1970) | publisher=Deep Listening | url=http://www.deeplistening.org/site/content/valerie-solanas-and-marilyn-monroe-recognition-their-desperation-1970-0 | accessdate=November 27, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813231042/http://www.deeplistening.org/site/content/valerie-solanas-and-marilyn-monroe-recognition-their-desperation-1970-0 | archive-date=13 August 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Marilyn\">{{cite web|title=Pauline Oliveros |publisher=Roaratorio |url=http://roaratorio.com/21.html |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426005046/http://roaratorio.com/21.html |archivedate=26 April 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Roland Orzabal]]: \"Dandelion\" references Monroe\n* [[A Perfect Circle]]: \"So Long, and Thanks for All the Fish\" references Monroe\n* [[Brianna Perry]]: \"[[Marilyn Monroe (Brianna Perry song)|Marilyn Monroe]]\"\n* [[Katy Perry]]: \"Hey Hey Hey\" references Monroe\n* [[Perez Prado]]: \"Marilyn Monroe [[Mambo (music)|Mambo]]\"\n* [[Los Prisioneros]]: \"\u00bfQui\u00e9n mat\u00f3 a Marilyn?\"\n* [[Brian Protheroe]]: \"Pinball\" references Monroe\n* [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]]: \"Wet Sand\" references her as Norma Jeane\n* [[Rihanna]]: \"[[Love Without Tragedy / Mother Mary]]\" references Monroe\n* [[Robbie Robertson]]: \"American Roulette\" references Monroe\n* [[Kelly Rowland]]: \"Stole\" references Monroe\n* [[Pete Seeger]]: \"Who Killed Norma Jean?\", debuted at his June 8, 1963 [[Carnegie Hall]] concert<ref>{{cite web|last=Bigger|first=Ken|title=Who Killed\u2026Norma Jean?|url=https://singout.org/2013/05/07/who-killed-norma-jean/|website=Sing Out!|date=May 7, 2013|access-date=August 30, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Brian Setzer Orchestra]]: \"Americano\" references Monroe\n* [[Sevdaliza]]: \"Marilyn Monroe\"\n* [[Sleeper (band)|Sleeper]]: \"Romeo Me\" references Monroe and Joe DiMaggio\n* [[Spice Girls]]: \"The Lady is a Vamp\" references Monroe\n* [[Stereophonics]]: \"She Takes Her Clothes Off\" references Monroe\n* [[Suede (band)|Suede]]: \"Heroine\" references Monroe\n* [[Tiffany (American singer)|Tiffany]]: \"Kiss the Ground\" references Monroe\n* [[SomeKindaWonderful|Jordy Towers]]: \"Don't Say It's Over\" references Monroe\n* [[Keith Urban]]: \"[[John Cougar, John Deere, John 3:16]]\" references Monroe\n* [[Tom Waits]]:\n** \"Jitterbug Boy\" references Monroe\n** \"A Sweet Little Bullet From a Pretty Blue Gun\" references Monroe\n** \"Hold On\" references Monroe\n* \"[[Marilyn Monroe (Pharrell Williams song)|Marilyn Monroe]]\" by [[Pharrell Williams]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|title=Pharrell's 'Marilyn Monroe' Is ''So'' Not What You Think It's About |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1723643/pharrell-marilyn-monroe-song/|website=[[MTV.com]]|date=March 6, 2014|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Robbie Williams]]: \"The Actor\" references Monroe\n\n==Music videos==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=September 2018}}\n[[File:Gentlemen Prefer Blondes Movie Trailer Screenshot (34).jpg|thumb|right|229px|The music video for \"Material Girl\" was inspired by Monroe's performance of the song \"[[Diamonds Are a Girl's Best Friend]]\" in the 1953 film ''[[Gentlemen Prefer Blondes (1953 film)|Gentlemen Prefer Blondes]]''.|alt=Marilyn Monroe in a pink gown, surrounded by men in tuxedos]]\n* \"[[Love Action (I Believe in Love)|Love Action]]\" by [[The Human League]] (1981): The music video features archival footage of Monroe and [[Arthur Miller]]\n* \"[[Girls Just Want to Have Fun#Music video|Girls Just Want to Have Fun]]\" by [[Cyndi Lauper]] (1983): A girl has a poster of Monroe on her wall\n* \"[[Photograph (Def Leppard song)#Music video|Photograph]]\" by [[Def Leppard]] (1983): An actress is glammed up as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* \"[[Fresh (Kool & the Gang song)#Music video|Fresh]]\" by [[Kool & the Gang]] (1984): The Fairy Godmother is glammed up as Monroe\n* \"In Neon\" by [[Elton John]] (1984): The music video features Monroe's [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] star\n* \"[[Material Girl#Music video|Material Girl]]\" by [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] (1985): The music video is a [[mimicry]] of Monroe's performance of the song \"[[Diamonds Are a Girl's Best Friend]]\" from the 1953 film ''[[Gentlemen Prefer Blondes (1953 film)|Gentlemen Prefer Blondes]]''. \"Well, my favorite scene in all of Monroe's movies is when she does that dance sequence for 'Diamonds Are a Girl's Best Friend'. And when it came time to do the video for the song [Material Girl], I said, I can just redo that whole scene and it will be perfect,\" she explained in a 1987 interview with ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]''. \"Marilyn was made into something not human in a way, and I can relate to that. Her sexuality was something everyone was obsessed with and that I can relate to. And there were certain things about her vulnerability that I'm curious about and attracted to.\"<ref name=\"feld\">{{harvnb|Feldman|2000|p=195}}</ref><ref name=\"tara1\">{{harvnb|Taraborrelli|2002|p=92}}</ref>\n* \"Sex as a Weapon\" by [[Pat Benatar]] (1985): The music video features archival footage of Monroe\n* \"[[Dancing on the Ceiling (Lionel Richie song)|Dancing on the Ceiling]]\" by [[Lionel Richie]] (1986): In the video, there is a reference to the film ''The Seven Year Itch'' when air blows a woman's skirt over her head\n* \"[[If You Were a Woman (And I Was a Man)]]\" by [[Bonnie Tyler]] (1986): The music video features a [[John Rambo|Rambo]]-like male soldier swinging on a rope as he lands on the stage while Tyler and the people on stage start to hold up a circle-and-cross female symbol who then transforms via ''[[An American Werewolf in London]]''-style special effects into a sultry Marilyn Monroe-like female vixen\n* \"[[Don't Drop Bombs]]\" by [[Liza Minnelli]] (1989): A poster of ''[[Gentlemen Prefer Blondes (1953 film)|Gentlemen Prefer Blondes]]'' can be seen on a wall of the room in the beginning of the video.\n* \"[[I Still Believe (Brenda K. Starr song)#Music videos|I Still Believe]]\" covered by Mariah Carey (1999): The music video recreates Monroe's 1954 performance for troops in Korea\n* \"[[Don't Forget About Us#Music video|Don't Forget About Us]]\" by [[Mariah Carey]] (2005): During a pool scene, Carey re-enacts a part from Monroe's film ''[[Something's Got to Give]]'' (1962) by singing with one leg up on the edge.<ref name=\"Vineyard4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1512753/marilyn-monroe-inspires-mariah-new-video.jhtml|title=Marilyn Monroe Inspires Mariah To Shed Clothes For New Video|website=[[MTV.com]]|accessdate=October 16, 2018|date=November 1, 2005|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard}}</ref> In an interview with [[MTV News]], Carey spoke of the re-enactment: \"That shot was totally and completely inspired by 'Something's Got to Give,' Marilyn Monroe's last movie that never got finished. It's an homage to her, because I've never seen anyone re-create it. So many people have emulated so many of Marilyn's classic moments, but it's just that I'm a big fan of hers, and I thought it was really pretty at night with the pool. No one could ever be as fabulous as Marilyn was, but it's in honor and homage to her.\"<ref name=\"Vineyard4\"/>\n* \"[[2 Hearts (Kylie Minogue song)#Music video|2 Hearts]]\" [[Kylie Minogue]] (2007): Minogue dresses as Monroe from ''Some Like It Hot''\n* \"[[Give Me All Your Luvin'#Music video|Give Me All Your Luvin']]\" by Madonna featuring [[Nicki Minaj]] and [[M.I.A. (singer)|M.I.A.]] (2012): Costumes worn in the video included a retro inspired look; the trio wore white lace dresses reminiscent of Madonna's look in her 20s, as well as [[Marilyn Monroe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fashionista.com/2012/02/watch-madonna-m-i-a-nicki-minaj-channel-cheerleaders-and-vintage-madonna-in-give-me-all-your-luvin|title=Watch: Madonna, M.I.A., Nicki Minaj Channel Cheerleaders And Vintage Madonna In 'Give Me All Your Luvin'|last=Phelan|first=Hayley|date=February 3, 2012|accessdate=October 16, 2018|work=Fashionista|quote=But the best part has to be when Madonna, M.I.A., and Nicki all break out the vintage white lace frocks, and Marilyn Monroe 'dos, for an awesome interpretation of an 80s-era Madonna.}}</ref>\n* \"[[National Anthem (Lana Del Rey song)#Music video|National Anthem]]\" by [[Lana Del Rey]] (2012): Del Rey apes Monroe's \"Happy Birthday, Mr. President\"<ref>[https://www.buzzfeed.com/bfeld/lana-del-rey-plays-marilyn-monroe-and-jackie-o-in \"Lana Del Rey Plays Marilyn Monroe And Jackie O\" ''BuzzFeed.com''] accessed August 23, 2012</ref>\n* \"[[Applause (Lady Gaga song)#Music video|Applause]]\" by [[Lady Gaga]] (2013): Gaga dresses like Monroe in ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* \"Below\" by [[White Lung]] (2016): A group of Marilyn Monroe look-a-likes can be seen at a movie theater\n* \"Marilyn Monroe\" by Danielle \"Dani\" Cohn (2017): The main theme of the video is about Monroe.\n* \"Coltrane\" by [[:sl:Anja Kotar|Anja Kotar]] (2017): Kotar channels Monroe in the video.\n* \"Paradise\" by [[Ofenbach (DJs)|Ofenbach]] featuring [[Benjamin Ingrosso]] (2018): Dorian Lo and C\u00e9sar de Rummel act as judges at a [[talent show]], in which an old Marilyn Monroe wannabe is one of the participants performing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2018/09/28/ofenbach-benjamin-ingrosso-paradise-official-music-video/|title=Sweden: Benjamin Ingrosso and Ofenbach release talent show inspired music video for 'Paradise'|work=[[Wiwibloggs]]|last=Muldoon|first=Padraig|date=September 28, 2018|access-date=October 16, 2018|quote=[The music video] sees the Ofenbach duo preside over a ''Got Talent''  style variety show while Benjamin preens and pampers himself backstage. A hotchpotch of acts take to the stage, ranging from a fearsome bodybuilder to an over the hill Marilyn Monroe wannabe.}}</ref>\n\n==Opera==\n* ''[[Marilyn (opera)|Marilyn]]'' (1980) by [[Lorenzo Ferrero]]<ref>[http://www.ricordi.it/catalogo/archivio-opere/lorenzo-ferrero/marilyn/view?set_language=en \"Casa Ricordi Catalogue\" ''ricordi.it'']</ref>\n* ''Marilyn'' (1993) by [[Ezra Laderman]] and [[Norman Rosten]] for the [[New York City Opera]]<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/08/arts/review-music-new-milieu-for-monroe-city-opera-s-marilyn.html?pagewanted=1 \"Review/Music; New Milieu for Monroe: City Opera's 'Marilyn'\" ''New York Times'' October 8, 1993] February 24, 2010</ref>\n* ''Marilyn Forever'' (2010) by [[Marilyn Bowering]] and [[Gavin Bryars]]<ref>[http://www.timescolonist.com/entertainment/Opera+goddess/3146887/story.html \"Opera for a Sex Goddess: Sooke Poet's Words About Marilyn Monroe Become Libretto\" ''The Victoria Times Colonist''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614003451/http://www.timescolonist.com/entertainment/Opera+goddess/3146887/story.html |date=14 June 2010 }} June 12, 2010</ref>\n\n==Photography==\n* [[Slim Aarons]], [[Richard Avedon]], [[Eve Arnold]], [[Luiz Carlos Barreto]], [[George Barris (photographer)|George Barris]], [[Peter Basch]], [[Cecil Beaton]], [[Otto Bettmann]], [[Carlyle Blackwell]], [[Cornell Capa]], [[Jack Cardiff]], [[Jock Carroll]], [[Henri Cartier-Bresson]], [[Larry Burrows]], [[Ed Clark (photographer)|Ed Clark]], [[William Claxton (photographer)|William Claxton]], [[Howell Conant]], [[David Conover]], [[Bruce Davidson (photographer)|Bruce Davidson]], [[Loomis Dean]], [[Alfred Eisenstaedt]], [[John Engstead]], [[Elliott Erwitt]], [[J. R. Eyerman]], [[Robert Frank]], [[Burt Glinn]], [[Allan Grant]], [[Milton H. Greene]], [[Ernst Haas]], [[Philippe Halsman]], [[Erich Hartmann (photographer)|Erich Hartmann]], [[Bob Henriques]], [[Jean Howard]], [[Frank Hurley]], [[George Hurrell]], [[Joseph Jasgur]], [[Tom Kelley (photographer)|Tom Kelley]], [[Douglas Kirkland]], [[Herman Leonard]], [[Harold Lloyd]], [[Lee Lockwood]], [[Jacques Lowe]], [[Arthur Marx]], [[Gjon Mili]], [[Richard C. Miller]], [[Earl Moran]], [[Inge Morath]], [[Nickolas Muray]], [[William B. Murphy]], [[Arnold Newman]], [[Gordon Parks]], [[Willy Rizzo]], [[Herb Scharfman]], [[Lawrence Schiller]], [[Paul Schutzer]], [[George Silk]], [[Peter Stackpole]], [[Len Steckler]], [[Bert Stern]], [[Phil Stern]], [[Dennis Stock]], [[Cecil W. Stoughton]], [[Bob Thomas (reporter)|Bob Thomas]], [[Gene Trindl]], [[John Vachon]], [[Delmar Watson]], [[Weegee]], [[Dan Weiner]], [[Leigh Wiener]], [[Laszlo Willinger]], [[Bob Willoughby]], [[Garry Winogrand]], [[William Woodfield]], [[Frank Worth]], and [[Jerome Zerbe]] were among the photographers who shot Monroe\n* The ''[[American Masters]]'' documentary \"Marilyn Monroe: Still Life\" claims that she was the most photographed person in history\n* ''[[Hachette Filipacchi Media U.S.|American Photo]]'' May/June 1997 issue was devoted to Monroe\n\nSee also: ''Marilyn Monroe'' by Eve Arnold, [[Abrams Books|Harry N. Abrams]] (2005), {{ISBN|0-8109-5933-X|978-0-8109-5933-0}}\n\nSee also: ''Marilyn Monroe and the Camera'' by Georges Belmont, Te Neues Publishing (2000), {{ISBN|3-8238-5467-4|978-3-8238-5467-8}}\n\nSee also: ''Marilyn by Andr\u00e9 de Dienes'' Steve Crist (Ed.), [[Taschen]] (2002), {{ISBN|3-8228-1199-8|978-3-8228-1199-3}}\n\nSee also: ''[[Life (magazine)|LIFE]]: Remembering Marilyn'' (2009), {{ISBN|1-60320-079-7|978-1-60320-079-0}}\n\nSee also: ''[[The Last Sitting]]'' by Bert Stern\n\nSee also: ''[[Marilyn: Norma Jean]]'' by [[Gloria Steinem]] with George Barris\n\n==Poetry==\n* [[Sherman Alexie]]: \"Tourists\" poem series (1997)\n* [[Steven Berkoff]]: \"You Remind Me of Marilyn Monroe\" (2009)\n* [[Frank Bidart]]: \"Marilyn Monroe\" (2006)\n* [[Marilyn Bowering]]: \"Anyone Can See I Love You\" (1987)\n* [[Ernesto Cardenal]]: \"Marilyn Monroe\" (1975)\n* [[Victor di Suvero]]: \"Marilyn, My Marilyn\" (2003)\n* [[Judy Grahn]]: \"I Have Come to Claim Marilyn Monroe's Body\" (1971)\n* [[Lyn Lifshin]]: \"Marilyn Monroe\" (1994)\n* [[Edwin Morgan (poet)|Edwin Morgan]]: \"The Death of Marilyn Monroe\" (1982)\n* [[Sharon Olds]]: \"The Death of Marilyn Monroe\" (1984)\n* [[Norman Rosten]]: \"Who Killed Norma Jeane?\" (1963)\n* [[Delmore Schwartz]]: \"Love and Marilyn Monroe\"\n* [[John Whitworth]]: \"Making Love to Marilyn Monroe\" (1990)\n\n==Radio==\n* ''[[Charlie McCarthy|The Charlie McCarthy Show]]'': \"November 9, 1952\", [[Edgar Bergen|Charlie McCarthy]] and Monroe announce their engagement\n* ''[[Old Harry's Game]]'': \"[[List of Old Harry's Game episodes|Olympics Special 2012, Episode One]]\", Thomas is crushed under an unconscious [[hippopotamus]] at Satan's Infernal Olympics; Scumspawn uses Monroe as an incentive for Thomas to extract himself from the hippo\n* ''Marilyn and Ella Backstage at the [[Mocambo (nightclub)|Mocambo]]'': a 2005 [[BBC Radio 4]] drama which recounts how Monroe helped Fitzgerald book a gig at the jazz club<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b07djzwp |title = BBC Radio 4 Extra \u2013 Bonnie Greer \u2013 Marilyn and Ella Backstage at the Mocambo}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n* ''[[American Gods (TV series)|American Gods]]'': \"Lemon Scented You\", during Mr. World's pitch to Wednesday, Media assumes the form of Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''<ref>[http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/article/american-gods-recap-season-1-episode-5-lemon-scented-you \"American Gods Recap Season 1, Episode 5, 'Lemon Scented You'\"] by Chuck Bowen [[Slant Magazine]] May 28, 2017</ref>\n* ''[[Angelina Ballerina: The Next Steps]]'': \"Angelina's Gift for Ms. Mimi\", a gust of wind makes Angelina ape the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Animaniacs]]'': \"Method to Her Madness\", Slappy and Skippy attend a [[method acting]] class Monroe is in\n* ''[[Archer (2009 TV series)|Archer]]'': \"Edie's Wedding\", Pam's attire and hairstyle for Edie's wedding makes her resemble Monroe\n* ''[[Arrested Development]]'':\n** \"What Goes Around\": Lucille Bluth sings \"Happy Birthday Mr. President\" to George Bluth in order to simulate him\n** \"A New Start\": Tobias F\u00fcnke settles on ''The Seven Year Itch''/Marilyn Monroe style of bed sheets\n* ''[[The Beverly Hillbillies]]'': \"The Clampetts Go Hollywood\", Elly May glams up as Monroe\n* ''[[Bewitched]]'': \"The Catnapper\", Endora tells Samantha that her \"mortal roommate seems to be getting \"the seven-year-itch\" five years early when he begins working nights\"\n* ''[[Blonde (2001 film)|Blonde]]'': a partially fictionalized account of Monroe's life\n* ''[[Brooklyn Nine-Nine]]'': \"The Therapist\", Charles Boyle says that \"The painting in the bathroom of Jesus standing over a vent with his robe blowing up like Marilyn Monroe?\"\n* ''[[Cagney & Lacey]]'': \"Jane Doe #37\", a girl Cagney and Lacey arrest gives her name as \"Norma Jeane Baker\", the name Monroe was known as growing up\n* ''The Celebrity Look-Alike Show'': In this special from 2003, a female audience member<ref>[https://www.archive.org/details/TheCelebrityLookalikeShow20030516 The Celebrity Look-A-Like Show (2003) (starts at 15:54/43:32)]</ref>is dressed like Monroe.\n* ''[[Children in Need 2007|Children in Need]]'' \"2007\": [[Wendi Peters]] performed a version of ''Diamonds Are a Girl's Best Friend'' from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' by adding \"I Am a Material Girl\" halfway through, then returning to the normal song.\n* ''[[Clone High]]'': Monroe hangs out at The Grassy Knoll with [[Nostradamus]]\n* ''[[Crazy Ex-Girlfriend]]'':\n** \"All Signs Point To Josh...or Is It Josh's Friend?\", Rebecca Bunch<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ck-UhvbCDAk Crazy Ex-Girlfriend | The Math of Love Triangles | The CW]</ref> in a blue dress and gloves sings in the music video \"The Math of Love Triangle\" is a payed homage to Monroe's ''Diamond's Are a Girl's Best Friend'' from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes''\n** \"I Need to Find My Frenemy\", \"The Math of Love Quadrangles\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=88QWRYHh4Vs The Math of Love Quadrangles \u2013 \"Crazy Ex-Girlfriend\"]</ref> is a reprise version of \"The Math of Love Triangles\" which itself is a parody of ''Diamonds Are a Girl's Best Friend'' from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes''\n* ''[[Criminal Minds]]'': \"Reflections of Desire\", Garcia quotes Monroe\n* ''[[The Critic]]'':\n** \"Marathon Mensch\", Jay imagines himself as a Monroe impersonator aping the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n** \"LA Jay\", a transvestite in a white dress offers to stand over a grate like Monroe in ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Designing Women]]'': \"Hard Hats and Lovers\", Charlene <ref>[http://www.designingwomenonline.com/Episodes/Summaries/049.php ''Designing Women'' Season 3 Episode 6 \"Hard Hats and Lovers\"]</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x3qqtab ''Designing Women'' Season 3 Episode 6 \"Hard Hats and Lovers\"]</ref> dresses as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch'' at a country club masquerade ball\n* ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'': \"Excited and Scared\", Ren\u00e9e dresses as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch'' for Halloween; Lee also dresses as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch'' as well\n* ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'': \"Blonde Leading the Blonde\", Dexter apes the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Dice (TV series)|Dice]]'': \"The Trial\", After being cast as [[James Monroe]] in a [[Musical theatre|musical]], Dice announces to Carmen: \"You are talking to President Marilyn Monroe\"\n* ''[[Doctor Who]]'': \"[[A Christmas Carol (Doctor Who)|A Christmas Carol]]\", The 11th Doctor ([[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]]) becomes engaged to Monroe\n* ''[[Drunk History]]'': \"Legends\", Monroe and [[Ella Fitzgerald]] form a lasting friendship<ref>[http://www.cc.com/video-clips/usj0u2/drunk-history-ella-fitzgerald-s-big-break Ella Fitzgerald's Big Break \u2013 Drunk History (Video Clip)]</ref>\n* ''[[El gran juego de la oca]]'': The Oquettes ape Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20001004095735/http://geocities.com/TelevisionCity/Set/4189/pruebas/prueba11.html El gran juego de la oca ''Marilyn Monroe']</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8scJKZGiT1s El Gran Juego de la Orca Oquettes imitan a Marilyn Monroe]</ref>\n* ''[[Elvis (1979 film)|Elvis]]'': Elvis tells his mother she is more beautiful than Monroe\n* ''[[Ernie Kovacs|The Ernie Kovacs Show]]'': [[Edie Adams]] regularly aped Monroe\n* ''[[Family Guy]]'': \"[[Mom's the Word]]\", Evelyn apes the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Family Ties]]'': \"I Know Jennifer's Boyfriend\", a poster of ''The Seven Year Itch'' is seen in the Keaton's house during Jennifer's 1950s-themed birthday party\n* ''[[Farscape]]'': \"Revenging Angel\", an animated version of<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AwrmZAS-u4Y Revenging Angel: Aeryn Animated \u2013 Farscape \u2013 The Jim Henson Company]</ref> Aeryn Sun briefly transforms into Marilyn Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Feud (TV series)|Feud: Bette and Joan]]'': \"Pilot\", Monroe (played by Alisha Soper)<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7hhgzz6TJPQ Marilyn Monroe in \"Feud: Bette and Joan\"]</ref> makes a guest appearance on the very first episode of the show as she accepts a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe award]] in 1960 for the classic romantic comedy film ''[[Some Like it Hot]]''.\n* ''Finding Marilyn'': An undeveloped reality series<ref>[http://realscreen.com/2012/04/12/eone-to-produce-reality-series-finding-marilyn Realscreen > Archive > eOne to produce reality series \"Finding Marilyn\"]</ref> emulating Monroe's journey to stardom, twelve young actresses travel to Los Angeles by competing for the chance to become the next Hollywood \"it\" girl.\n* ''[[Frasier]]'': \"Room Full of Heroes\", Martin, as Joe DiMaggio, references Monroe; Daphne, as [[Elton John]], references \"Candle in the Wind\"\n* ''[[Full House]]'': \"Mad Money\", Jesse brings home a Monroe impersonator\n* ''[[Futurama]]'':\n** \"[[I Dated a Robot]]\", a teenager makes out with \"Marilyn Monrobot\"\n** \"[[Attack of the Killer App]]\", Monroe's dress blowing up scene is spoofed\n** \"[[The Mutants Are Revolting]]\", a girl's dress blows upward like Monroe in ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Gilligan's Island]]'': \"The Producer\", Ginger glams up as Monroe\n* ''[[Gilmore Girls]]'': \"Red Light on the Wedding Night\", a waiter at the club Lorelei has her bachelorette party is dressed as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[The Girls Next Door]]'':\n** \"Mutiny on the Booty\", [[Holly Madison]] is watching ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes''\n** \"Family Affair\", The late [[Hugh Hefner]], [[Holly Madison]] and the dog are in bed watching a scene from<ref>[https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x3x1iqy The Girls Next Door S3E09 - Family Affair (starts at 20:35/23:20)]</ref> ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes''\n* ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'': \"Girls (and Boys) on Film\", Marley Rose and Wade \"Unique\" Adams with The New Directions Girls sings<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M59l9Qcc480 GLEE \u2013 Diamond's are a Girl's Best Friend/Material Girl (Full Performance) (Official Music Video) HD]</ref> ''Diamond's are a Girl's Best Friend'' from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' along with a mashup of ''Material Girl'' by [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n* ''[[Golden Girls|The Golden Girls]]'': \"Letters to Gorbachev\", Blanche apes \"[[Happy Birthday, Mr. President]]\" to [[Mikhail Gorbachev]]\n* ''[[Gossip Girl]]'': \"G.G.\", Serena van der Woodsen<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dhmsc3Z09ko Serena's dream sequence (GG 100th episode)]</ref> dresses as Monroe from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' including Blair Waldorf dressing like [[Audrey Hepburn]] as Holly Golightly from ''[[Breakfast at Tiffany's (film)|Breakfast at Tiffany's]]'' in a dream sequence as part of the show's 100th episode\n* ''[[Growing Pains]]'': \n**\"Happy Halloween: Part 2\", a character dresses as Monroe\n**\"Carol's Carnival\", Carol Seaver ([[Tracey Gold]])<ref>[https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x6rx8pj Growing Pains S06 -Ep22 Carol's Carnival (starts at 17:17/27:31)]</ref> dresses as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch'' as a vent from below blows her dress up like the famous scene\n* ''[[Happy Endings (TV series)|Happy Endings]]'': \"Spooky Endings\", Alex dresses as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch'' for a Halloween party\n* ''[[Hart of Dixie]]'': \"Walkin' After Midnight\", Lemon dresses as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch'' for a Halloween party\n* ''[[Here Comes Honey Boo Boo]]'': \"A Very Boo Halloween\", Mama June (a.k.a. June Shannon) dresses as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch'' in the episode from 2013\n* ''[[Hey Arnold!]]'': \"The Beeper Queen\", Helga Pataki's mother Miriam sings \"Beepers Are a Girl's Best Friend\" as a parody of \"Diamond's Are a Girl's Best Friend\" <ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J3m6sr6VGfs BEEPERS ARE A GIRL'S BEST FRIEND]</ref> from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' in a commercial for Big Bob's Beepers\n* ''[[The Honeymooners]]'': \"A Woman's Work Is Never Done\", Ralph references Monroe\n* ''[[I Love Lucy]]'': \"Ricky's Movie Offer\", Lucy and Ethel think Ricky's script has a Monroe-type part, and ask Fred which one of them looks like her; Lucy glams up as Monroe\n* ''[[Introducing Dorothy Dandridge]]'': In one scene, Earl Mills discovers Dandridge under a piano along with two other rising stars [[Ava Gardner]] and Marilyn Monroe\n* ''[[It's a Living]]'': In \"Her Back to the Future\", Dot dresses like Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch'' during Nancy's dream\n* ''[[It's Worth What?]]'': A Marilyn Monroe<ref>[http://theblogisright.blogspot.com/2011/07/its-worth-what-review.html \"It's Worth What?\" Review + A Special Announcement]</ref> impersonator wearing white gloves makes an appearance\n* ''[[I've Got a Secret]]'': \"November 11, 1953\", Gene Scanlon had a date with Marilyn Monroe (as she actually paid for the tab)\n* ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'': \"Ghost Bummer\", Jessie dresses as Monroe for Halloween<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rCuaNJ0NcMI \"''Jessie'' Season 3 Premieres with Monstober Episode \u2013 Exclusive Clip\" ''www.youtube.com''] Retrieved November 1, 2013</ref>\n* ''[[Keeping Up with the Kardashians]]'': \"Paparazzi & Papas\", Khlo\u00e9 asks her grandmother's prospective dates if they like Monroe\n* ''[[The Kennedys (miniseries)|The Kennedys]]'': Monroe is obsessed with [[John F. Kennedy]] in the days leading up to her suicide but is warned against blackmailing him.\n* ''[[Last Man Standing (U.S. TV series)|Last Man Standing]]'': \"Adrenaline\", Mike references Monroe on his [[Webcast]]\n* ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]'': \"Bombshell\", a prescription bottle found by Logan and Wheeler is made out to Monroe's birth name, Norma Mortensen; Merritt references Monroe\n* ''[[Legends of Tomorrow|DC's Legends of Tomorrow]]'':\n** \"Legends of To-Meow-Meow\", Magical fugitive Charlie impersonates Monroe\n** \"Terms of Service\", Magical fugitive Charlie impersonates Monroe\n* ''[[Lethal Weapon (TV series)|Lethal Weapon]]'' (TV series): \"Fools Rush In\", A Monroe look a like personality is wearing the famous white dress from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''Le Juste Prix'' (Belgium): Host [[:fr:Micha\u00ebl Dufour|Micha\u00ebl Dufour]] dresses as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''.<ref>[http://www.facebook.com/pg/Le-Jute-PrixBelge-147141388631666/photos/?tab=album&album_id=178537195492085 Le Juste Prix (Belge)]</ref>\n* ''[[Let's Sing and Dance]]'': [[Rosemary Shrager]] and [[Kim Woodburn]]<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7ctURZwKK80 Kim Woodburn & Rosemary Shrager perform 'Diamonds Are a Girl's Best Friend' | Red Nose Day 2013]</ref> performed ''Diamonds Are a Girl's Best Friend'' from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' in 2013\n* ''[[Love, Marilyn]]''\n* ''[[Lucifer (TV series)|Lucifer]]'': \"Lucifer, Stay. Good Devil\", Monroe's white dress is seen.\n* ''[[Mad Men]]'':\n** \"Maidenform\", Monroe and [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis|Jackie Kennedy]] inspire the agency's campaign for [[Playtex]]\n** \"Six Month Leave\", Monroe's death affects Hollis, Joan, and the office girls\n* ''Marilyn & Bobby: Her Final Affair''\n* ''[[Marilyn and Me]]''\n* ''Marilyn Monroe: The Final Days''\n* ''[[Marilyn: The Untold Story]]''\n* ''[[Married... with Children]]'': \"It's a Bundyful Life\", Al asks his guardian angel if Monroe is laughing at him because he caved to Peg's demand that he toss his ''[[Playboy]]''s\n* ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'': \"Bombshells\", Hawkeye and Charles start a rumor that Monroe is coming to the 4077 to thank the staff for caring for her cousin\n* ''[[Merrie Melodies]]'': \"Knight-mare Hare\", as [[Bugs Bunny]] goes to another castle, he meets the residence of a warlock (or wizard) named Merlin of Monroe his name in particular is a pun on Marilyn Monroe\n* ''[[Modern Family]]'': \"[[Modern Family (season 10)|Good Grief]]\", Gloria Pritchett<ref>[https://blog.everlasting-star.net/2018/10/celebrities/sophia-vergara-brings-marilyn-to-modern-family/ Sophia Vergara Brings Marilyn to 'Modern Family']</ref>([[Sofia Vergara]]) is dressed as Monroe from ''[[Gentlemen Prefer Blondes]]'' in a Halloween episode\n* ''[[Movies Rock]]'': [[Nicole Scherzinger]] performed a version of ''Diamonds Are a Girl's Best Friend'' from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' which paid tribute to the strong relationship between film and music\n* ''[[Mr. Belvedere]]'': \"Mumsy\", Kevin Owens has a movie poster of ''The Seven Year Itch'' hanging on the wall in his apartment\n* ''[[The Muppets Go to the Movies]]'': [[Miss Piggy]] performs the song \"Heatwave\" in a costume reminiscent of the one worn by Monroe in ''There's No Business like Show Business''\n* ''[[The Muppet Show]]'':\n** \"Season 1, Episode 20\", [[Valerie Harper]]<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4B8By1FOCd0 Muppets \u2013 Valerie Harper \u2013 Broadway Baby]</ref> donning a short blonde wig and brown dress briefly does an impression of Monroe during her opening number ''Broadway Baby''\n** \"Season 4, Episode 23\", [[Miss Piggy]] and [[Carol Channing]]<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9qiZG05gymc Muppet Songs: Carol Channing and Miss Piggy \u2013 Diamonds are a Girl's Best Friend]</ref> sing ''Diamonds are a Girl's Best Friend'' from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' as the closing number\n* ''[[Muppets Tonight]]'': \"Season 1, Episode 9\", [[Miss Piggy]] and [[Whoopi Goldberg]] sing ''Diamonds are a Girl's Best Friend'' from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' as the closing number\n* ''[[The Name's the Same]]'':\n** \"September 3, 1952\", a celebrity guest [[Johnny Mercer]] wants to be Marilyn Monroe\n** \"November 19, 1952\", a contestant's actual name is Marilyn Monroe\n** \"January 12, 1954\", two contestants' actual names are Marilyn Monroe and Joe DiMaggio\n** \"June 22, 1954\", [[Van Johnson]]'s \"secret wish\" is for Marilyn to sit on his lap\n** \"August 31, 1954\", [[Charles Coburn]]'s \"secret wish\" is to dance the [[Rhumba|rumba]] with Monroe as he did in ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes''\n* ''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]'':\n** \"Kill Ari, Part 1\", DiNozzo has Caitlin imitate the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch'' in his fantasy\n** \"Minimum Security\", Ducky tells Abby his mother wears nothing to bed but [[Chanel No. 5]] ever since Monroe said it's the only thing she wears to bed\n** \"Witch Hunt\", Abby dresses as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch'' for Halloween\n* ''[[The Next Best Thing (TV series)|The Next Best Thing: Who is the Greatest Celebrity Impersonator?]]'': A celebrity impersonator named Jodi Fleisher impersonates Marilyn Monroe\n* ''[[Norma Jean & Marilyn]]''\n* ''[[The Norm Show]]'': \"Norm vs. Fear\", a girl dressed up like Monroe's character from ''The Seven Year Itch'' fixing a light as Taylor Clayton (Nikki Cox) shuts the door<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=txXFUM6bthc ''The Norm Show'' S02E18 Norm vs. Fear]</ref><ref>[https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x4cjlsx ''Norm'' aka ''The Norm Show'' \u2013 2 \u2013 18 \u2013 Norm Vs Fear]</ref>\n* ''[[Nip/Tuck]]'': \"Joyce & Sharon Monroe\", two Monroe [[Look-alike]]s want to look more like her\n* ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]'': \"Pictures of You\", Brooke Davis impersonates Monroe for a class assignment\n* ''[[Parenthood (2010 TV series)|Parenthood]]'' (TV series): \"Opening Night\", Sydney Graham is dressed as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Phil Spector (film)|Phil Spector]]'': Spector speculates on Monroe's death during his first meeting with Linda\n* ''[[The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show]]'': Cindy Curbstone is patterned after Monroe.\n* ''[[The Pretender (TV series)|The Pretender]]'': \"Curious Jarod\", Jarod reviews a Simulation of the night of Monroe's death in which his younger self speculates as if \"Norma Jean\" or \"Marilyn\" was possibly murdered and why\n* ''[[Pretty Little Liars]]'': \"This Is a Dark Ride\", Hannah Marin dresses as Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch'' in a Halloween episode\n* ''[[Quantum Leap]]'':\n** \"What Price Gloria?\", at a mirror, Gloria Collins says to \"Eat your heart out, Marilyn.\"\n** \"Goodbye Norma Jean\", Sam leaps into the body of Monroe's chauffeur\n* ''[[Quincy, M.E.]]'': \"A Star Is Dead\", Quincy investigates the death of a Monroe-like movie star\n* ''[[The Rat Pack (film)|The Rat Pack]]'': Monroe gets introduced to [[John F. Kennedy]] through [[Frank Sinatra]].\n* ''[[The Real Ghostbusters]]'':\n** \"Apocalypse -- What, Now?\", A female mannequin in a blue dress briefly imitates a pose of Monroe from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n** \"Janine, You've Changed\", Janine insinuates that she has claimed Monroe\n* ''[[Red Dwarf]]'': \"The Last Day\", The famous white dress billowing up image is printed on the box for the Marilyn Monroe robot kit\n* ''[[Robot Chicken]]'':\n** \"Rodigitti\", [[Roddy Piper|\"Rowdy\" Roddy Piper's]] kilt blows upward as he stands on a drain while he pushes it back down\n** \"Up, Up, and Buffet\", in this brief segment called \"Candle With Too Much Wind\" Monroe is relieved that they went this route given the movie ''The Seven Year Itch''\n* ''[[Roseanne (TV series)|Roseanne]]'': \"Skeleton in the Closet\", Nancy dresses as Monroe for the diner's Halloween party\n* ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'': Ivy Winters (Dustin Winters) dressed as one of the \"Two Little Girls from Little Rock\" from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' in a segment of ''[[Match Game|Snatch Game]]'' (Season 5, Episode 5)\n* ''[[Sabrina the Teenage Witch (1996 TV series)|Sabrina the Teenage Witch]]'': \"A Halloween Story\", one of the guests at Harvey's Halloween party is dressed as Monroe\n* ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'':\n** [[Teri Garr]] played Monroe with [[Joe Piscopo]] as John F. Kennedy (Season 9, Episode 5)\n** [[Mary Gross]] played Monroe as a recurring character (1981\u20131985)\n** [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] played Monroe (Season 11, Episode 1)\n*** aped \"Happy Birthday, Mr. President\" (Season 18, Episode 11)\n** [[Charlize Theron]] as Monroe with [[Jimmy Fallon]] as Joe DiMaggio (Season 26, Episode 4)\n** [[Abby Elliott]] as Monroe with [[Helen Mirren]] as [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] (Season 36, Episode 19)\n** [[Nasim Pedrad]] as Monroe in an [[SNL Digital Short]] (Season 37, Episode 9)\n* ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]'': \"My Tormented Mentor\", in one of the fantasy sequences; the male surgeons briefly dream that Dr. Grace Miller ([[Bellamy Young]]) is Monroe<ref>[https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x6kv1bs Scrubs S03E15 My Tormented Mentor]</ref>\n* ''[[The Secret Life of Marilyn Monroe]]'': a TV mini-series where it chronicles Monroe's family life, her relationship with her mother Gladys Baker and how she succeeded in hiding her most intimate secrets from the press and an invasive world.\n* ''Semi-Homemade Cooking'': Host/Chef [[Sandra Lee (chef)|Sandra Lee]] is dressed as Monroe from<ref>[https://www.foodnetwork.com/shows/semi-homemade-cooking-with-sandra-lee/episodes/halloween2 Halloween | Semi-Homemade Cooking | Food Network Season 9, Episode 7]</ref>''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' in a Halloween episode (Season 9, Episode 7)\n* ''[[Seinfeld]]'': [[The Note (Seinfeld)|\"The Note\"]], George references Monroe after Kramer claims he saw Joe DiMaggio at Dinky Donuts\n* ''[[Sheep in the Big City]]'': \"Be Still My Bleating Heart\", Sheep's wool briefly goes up in a Marilyn Monroe-like pose while standing over a subway vent\n* ''[[Sing Your Face Off]]'' (Week 6): Former soap opera actress [[Lisa Rinna]] dressed as Monroe from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' in an episode\n* ''[[The Simpsons]]'':\n** \"[[The Homer They Fall]]\", a picture of Monroe is on a jacket\n** \"[[Rosebud (The Simpsons)|Rosebud]]\", Smithers imagines Mr. Burns singing \"[[Happy Birthday to You]]\" to him [[List of French words and phrases used by English speakers|\u00e0 la]] \"Happy Birthday, Mr. President\"\n*** a [[Reversal film|slide photo]] of Mr. Burns shows him aping the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch''\n** \"[[Thirty Minutes over Tokyo]]\" features a Monroe robot\n** \"[[Treehouse of Horror XIV]]\", Professor Frink tells Bart and Lisa his father \"worked on the [[atom bomb]] by day, slept with Marilyn Monroe by night, and sold secrets to the Russians at lunch\"\n** Moe apes the \"subway grate\" pose from ''The Seven Year Itch'' on Disk 4 of the Season 6 DVD set menu\n** Dr. Marvin Monroe's original first name was Marilyn\n* ''[[Smash (U.S. TV series)|Smash]]'': Main plot concerns the planning of a [[Bombshell (musical)|Broadway]] [[Bombshell (Smash album)|musical]] about Monroe\n* ''[[Sordid Lives: The Series]]'': \"The Fall and Rise of Brother Boy\", Ty is shown Monroe's [[ukulele]] from ''Some Like It Hot''.\n* ''[[The Starlet]]'': Ten aspiring actresses live together in a house once owned by Monroe.\n* ''[[Time Machine (game show)|Time Machine]]'': a pic of Monroe<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BtLO53bOepk TIME MACHINE opening credits game show]</ref> on  the cover of a December 1953 issue of ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine along with a still of her from the classic film ''[[The Seven Year Itch]]'' can briefly be seen during the opening credits during the second format of the show.\n* ''[[Trivia Trap]]'': A pic of Monroe<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wWkKb0AZb5c ''Trivia Trap'' ABC Daytime 1984 Premiere (October 8th 1984)]</ref> can briefly be seen during the first season opening credits.\n* ''[[T.J. Hooker]]'': \"Target: Hooker\", a male drag performer impersonates Monroe.<ref>[http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x5vn6tz TJ Hooker S04E06 Target Hooker]</ref>\n* ''[[Tosh.0]]'': \"Boy in Black Face\", a little girl dresses as Monroe in a spoof of ''The Seven Year Itch''.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XyY56Ei1Rp8 Tosh.0 \u2013 September 25, 2012 \u2013 Blackface Kid \u2013 YouTube]</ref><ref>[https://www.cc.com/sqq59j/tosh_0-extended-interview---blackface-kid Extended Interview \u2013 Blackface Kid's Web Redemption \u2013 Tosh.0 (Video Clip)]</ref><ref>[https://www.cc.com/video-clips/l11uc6/tosh-0-web-redemption---blackface-kid---uncensored Web Redemption \u2013 Black Face Kid \u2013 Uncensored \u2013 Tosh.0 (Video Clip)]</ref>\n* ''[[To Tell the Truth]]'':\n** \"April 7, 1967\", Monroe's first husband James Dougherty<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AEOmYzYmZ5w Marilyn Monroe \u2013 James Dougherty(first husband) on TO TELL THE TRUTH]</ref> appears as a \"central character\" in this episode.\n** \"November 1990\", Monroe impersonator Jimmy James<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PbAJoN652AM JIMMY JAMES on To Tell the Truth Part 1 (11/90)]</ref><ref>[https://wwww.youtube.com/watch?v=QuN40yK08hg JIMMY JAMES on To Tell the Truth Part 2 (11/90)]</ref> appears as a \"central character\" in this episode along with singing his version of \"I want to be loved by you\".\n* ''[[Two and a Half Men]]'': \"Untainted by Filth\", Charlie has a flashback of drunken Alan in a blonde wig singing \"Happy Birthday, Mr. President\" \u00e0 la Monroe.\n* ''[[Warehouse 13]]'': \"Love Sick\", Monroe's hairbrush turns hair platinum blonde when used\n* ''[[What's My Line?]]'':\n** \"January 3, 1954\", Art Gaisor sells Marilyn Monroe Calendars\n** \"September 12, 1954\", [[Natasha Lytess]] (as Miss Tala Forman) is Marilyn Monroe's Drama Coach\n** \"September 18, 1955\", Monroe's former husband [[Joe Dimaggio]] appears as a mystery guest\n** \"June 12, 1955\", [[Tom Ewell]] appears as a mystery guest and promotes the film ''The Seven Year Itch''\n** \"July 1, 1956\", Judge Seymour Rabinowitz married both Marilyn Monroe and [[Arthur Miller]]\n** \"August 21, 1960\", mystery guest [[Buddy Hackett]] signs in as \"Marilyn Monroe\" (however, it was written as \"Maralyn Monroe\")\n* ''[[Your Face Sounds Familiar]]'': some international versions features female stars dressing up as Monroe from ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes''.\n* ''[[Zoey 101]]'': \"Haunted House\", Zoey dresses as Monroe for Halloween\n\n==Theater==\n\n'''By [[Arthur Miller]], Monroe's third husband:'''\n* ''[[After the Fall (play)|After the Fall]]'' (1964) \u2013 The play and its main characters, Maggie and Quentin, are based on Monroe and Miller and their marriage\n* ''[[Finishing the Picture]]'' (2004) \u2013 The play is based on Miller's experiences of making ''[[The Misfits (1961 film)|The Misfits]]'' (1961), with Kay being based on Monroe\n\n'''Plays and musicals based on Monroe's life or with Monroe as a central character:'''\n* ''Marilyn'' (1975) by [[Adam Darius]]\n* ''[[Insignificance (film)|Insignificance]]'' (1982) by [[Terry Johnson (dramatist)|Terry Johnson]]: The Actress is based on Monroe\n* ''[[Marilyn! the Musical]]'' (1983) by Jacques Wilson and [[Mort Garson]]\n* ''[[Marilyn: An American Fable]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Strawhead]]'' (1986) by [[Norman Mailer]] and [[Richard Hannum]]\n* ''Miss Golden Dreams'' (2001) by [[Joyce Carol Oates]]\n* ''[[Marilyn Forever Blonde]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Marilyn and Ella]]'' (2008) by [[Bonnie Greer]]\n* ''Marilyn's 2nd Chance'' (2009), and ''Marilyn Monroe, My Secret'' (2013) by [[Willard Manus]]\n* ''Norma Jeane: The Musical'' (2013): songs written by [[Jay Aston]]\n* ''Marilyn: My Secret'' with [[Erin Gavin]] as Monroe in the first run (2015)<ref>https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/scots-actress-gets-thumbs-up-marilyn-5229072</ref>\n'''Plays and musicals with Monroe as a minor character or referenced to:'''\n* ''[[Will Success Spoil Rock Hunter? (play)|Will Success Spoil Rock Hunter?]]'' (1955): Monroe's lookalike [[Jayne Mansfield]] plays a dumb actress who starts her own production company.{{sfn|Spoto|2001|p=338}} Prior to the play's production and premiere, Monroe had told [[Milton Greene]] about her grievances with [[20th Century Fox]], with Greene suggesting that they start their own production company.{{sfn|Spoto|2001|pp=158\u2013159, 252\u2013254}} Announcing its foundation in a press conference in January 1955, Monroe had stated that she was \"tired of the same old sex roles. I want to do better things. People have scope, you know.\"{{sfn|Spoto|2001|p=303}} She had asserted that she was no longer under contract to Fox, as the studio had not fulfilled its duties, such as paying her the promised bonus for ''The Seven Year Itch''.{{sfn|Spoto|2001|pp=302\u2013303}} This would begin a year-long legal battle between her and the studio,{{sfn|Spoto|2001|pp=301\u2013302}} that saw her being ridiculed by the press and by this play, ''Will Success Spoil Rock Hunter?'', which was written by ''[[The Seven Year Itch]]'' writer [[George Axelrod]].{{sfn|Spoto|2001|p=338}}\n* ''[[Blood Brothers (musical)|Blood Brothers]]'' (1983): two songs called \"Marilyn Monroe\"\n* ''[[Wilhelm Reich in Hell]]'' (1987): Monroe is a character\n* ''Nobody Dies on Friday'' (1998) by [[Robert Brustein]]: About [[Lee Strasberg]] and the [[Actors Studio]], with Monroe as a supporting character\n\n==Video games==\n* ''[[Bill & Ted's Excellent Video Game Adventure]]'': A pic of Monroe can be seen in a phone book with the numbers 555-1155 in blue and the numbers 555-1764 in red<ref>[http://nerdbacon.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Screen-Shot-2015-04-10-at-1.02.55-PM.png Bill & Ted's Excellent Video Game Adventure \u2013 NES]</ref>\n* ''[[Bugs Bunny: Lost in Time]]'': A sorcerer named Merlin Munroe is a pun on Marilyn Monroe\n* ''Discworld II: Mortality Bytes!'': The Milkmaid (a Marilyn Monroe look a like) stands on a grate as her dress billows up\n* ''[[Double Dragon V: The Shadow Falls]]'': An undead skeleton character named Bones has one of his likes in Marrowlyn Monroe, a parody of her first name.\n* ''[[Final Fight Revenge]]'': [[Poison (Final Fight)|Poison]]<ref>[http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/finalfight/poison-7.png Final Fight Revenge Poison]</ref> in a light pink dress apes the Marilyn Monroe pose from ''[[The Seven Year Itch]]''.\n* ''Gigi'': The girl<ref>[http://pinrepair.com/gtb/gigi.htm 1963 Gottlieb Gigi pinball (1 player replay)]</ref> on the backglass cover is supposed to resemble Marilyn Monroe\n* ''Hard Evidence: The Marilyn Monroe Files'': Four characters<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5586604/ Hard Evidence: The Marilyn Monroe Files (Video Game 1995)]</ref> (the cop, the lawyer, the coroner and the investigative reporter) try to investigate her tragic death from a different angle to get to the truth.\n* ''Hisshou Pachinko *Pachi-Slot Kouryoku Series Vol 3: CR Marilyn Monroe'': Translated as ''Winning Pachinko Mari ly N Monroe'', a virtually marine-themed paci-slot game, features Monroe.\n* ''[[Shinobi (video game)|Shinobi]]'' (1987): Posters of Monroe<ref>[http://burnaway.org/interview/from-picasso-to-Warhol-to-sega-ashley-andersons-shinobi-Marilyn From Picasso to Warhol to Sega: Ashley Anderson's Shinobi Marilyn]</ref> can be found plastered on a wall in the second third of the first level.\n* ''[[Taxi (pinball)|Taxi (pinball game)]]'' (1988): A blonde Marilyn Monroe-like image in a red dress can be seen as a taxi passenger<ref>[http://www.flippers.be/pinball/williams/taxi/taxi.html Williams Taxi]</ref> in both the backglass and playfield. But due to copyright infringement at the time, she was later changed to a brunette woman named Lola<ref>[http://www.ipdb.org/showpic.pl?id=2505&picno=15971 'Taxi'  Image title: ''Backglass \u2013 Lola'']</ref>\n* ''Jigoku no Renshuu'': Translated as ''Hell of Exercises'', Monroe wearing a white choker makes an appearance in the game<ref>[http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/jigoku-no-renshuu-mondai/ Jigoku No Renshuu Mondai \"Hardcore Gaming 101\"]</ref>\n* ''[[The Joker's Wild]]'' (1994): A Marilyn Monroe-type<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20050408103637/http://www.classicgameshows.com/cd-i/tjw.html The Joker's Wild CD-I]</ref> personality photo can be seen in the category \"Sex Symbols\".\n* ''[[Kantai Collection]]'': {{USS|Saratoga|CV-3|2}}'s standard pose of pushing her skirt down as it's blown upward by wind is inspired by a famous and iconic pose by Marilyn Monroe, taken from the movie ''The Seven Year Itch''.\n* ''[[Yo-kai Watch 2]]'': An in-game version of Marilyn Monroe called \"Mary Ronmo\", who starred in the movie \"Gentlemen Endure Prawns\", a spoof of ''Gentlemen Prefer Blondes''. A sidequest involves finding her famous [[White dress of Marilyn Monroe|red dress]], which she wore in a scene in which her dress was blown upwards.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Marilyn Monroe filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n===Works cited===\n* {{citation | last = Feldman | first = Christopher | title = Billboard book of number 2 singles | year = 2000 | publisher = Watson-Guptill | isbn = 0-8230-7695-4 | url = https://archive.org/details/billboardbookofn00chri }}\n* {{Cite book | last = Spoto | first = Donald | authorlink = Donald Spoto | title = Marilyn Monroe: The Biography | year = 2001 | publisher = Cooper Square Press | isbn = 978-0-8154-1183-3 | ref = harv | url = https://archive.org/details/marilynmonroe00dona }}\n* {{c